  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: "1: David Learns of Saul\u2019s Death"
      title: "David Learns of Saul\u2019s Death"
      number: 1
      content: '  After the death of Saul, David returned from his victory over the
        Amalekites and spent two days in Ziklag. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "On the third day a man arrived from Saul\u2019s army camp. He had
        torn his clothes and put dirt on his head to show that he was in mourning.
        He fell to the ground before David in deep respect.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CWhere have you come from?\u201D David asked.\u201CI escaped
        from the Israelite camp,\u201D the man replied.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CWhat happened?\u201D David demanded. \u201CTell me how the
        battle went.\u201DThe man replied, \u201COur entire army fled from the battle.
        Many of the men are dead, and Saul and his son Jonathan are also dead.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CHow do you know Saul and Jonathan are dead?\u201D David demanded
        of the young man.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The man answered, \u201CI happened to be on Mount Gilboa, and there
        was Saul leaning on his spear with the enemy chariots and charioteers closing
        in on him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "When he turned and saw me, he cried out for me to come to him. \u2018How
        can I help?\u2019 I asked him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CHe responded, \u2018Who are you?\u2019\u201C\u2018I am an Amalekite,\u2019
        I told him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CThen he begged me, \u2018Come over here and put me out of my
        misery, for I am in terrible pain and want to die.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CSo I killed him,\u201D the Amalekite told David, \u201Cfor
        I knew he couldn\u2019t live. Then I took his crown and his armband, and
        I have brought them here to you, my lord.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'David and his men tore their clothes in sorrow when they heard the
        news. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "They mourned and wept and fasted all day for Saul and his son Jonathan,
        and for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s army and the nation of Israel,
        because they had died by the sword that day.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then David said to the young man who had brought the news, \u201CWhere
        are you from?\u201DAnd he replied, \u201CI am a foreigner, an Amalekite,
        who lives in your land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CWhy were you not afraid to kill the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anointed one?\u201D David asked.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Then David said to one of his men, \u201CKill him!\u201D So the man
        thrust his sword into the Amalekite and killed him. "
      comments: []
    - name: "16: David\u2019s Song for Saul and Jonathan"
      title: "David\u2019s Song for Saul and Jonathan"
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CYou have condemned yourself,\u201D David said, \u201Cfor you
        yourself confessed that you killed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anointed one.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Then David composed a funeral song for Saul and Jonathan, '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'and he commanded that it be taught to the people of Judah. It is
        known as the Song of the Bow, and it is recorded in The Book of Jashar.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:18 '
        content: Or <b>The Book of the Upright.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Your pride and joy, O Israel, lies dead on the hills!Oh, how the
        mighty heroes have fallen!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Don\u2019t announce the news in Gath,don\u2019t proclaim it in the
        streets of Ashkelon,or the daughters of the Philistines will rejoiceand the
        pagans will laugh in triumph.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'O mountains of Gilboa,let there be no dew or rain upon you,nor fruitful
        fields producing offerings of grain.[[COMMENT(0)]]For there the shield of
        the mighty heroes was defiled;the shield of Saul will no longer be anointed
        with oil.  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:21 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'The bow of Jonathan was powerful,and the sword of Saul did its mighty
        work.They shed the blood of their enemiesand pierced the bodies of mighty
        heroes.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'How beloved and gracious were Saul and Jonathan!They were together
        in life and in death.They were swifter than eagles,stronger than lions.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'O women of Israel, weep for Saul,for he dressed you in luxurious
        scarlet clothing,in garments decorated with gold.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Oh, how the mighty heroes have fallen in battle!Jonathan lies dead
        on the hills.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'How I weep for you, my brother Jonathan!Oh, how much I loved you!And
        your love for me was deep,deeper than the love of women!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: Oh, how the mighty heroes have fallen!Stripped of their weapons, they
        lie dead.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David Anointed King of Judah'
      title: David Anointed King of Judah
      number: 1
      content: "  After this, David asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CShould
        I move back to one of the towns of Judah?\u201D\u201CYes,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        replied.Then David asked, \u201CWhich town should I go to?\u201D\u201CTo
        Hebron,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> answered.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "David\u2019s two wives were Ahinoam from Jezreel and Abigail, the
        widow of Nabal from Carmel. So David and his wives "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'and his men and their families all moved to Judah, and they settled
        in the villages near Hebron. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Then the men of Judah came to David and anointed him king over the
        people of Judah.When David heard that the men of Jabesh-gilead had buried
        Saul, '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "he sent them this message: \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        bless you for being so loyal to your master Saul and giving him a decent
        burial. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> be loyal to you in return and
        reward you with his unfailing love! And I, too, will reward you for what
        you have done. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: Ishbosheth Proclaimed King of Israel'
      title: Ishbosheth Proclaimed King of Israel
      number: 7
      content: "Now that Saul is dead, I ask you to be my strong and loyal subjects
        like the people of Judah, who have anointed me as their new king.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But Abner son of Ner, the commander of Saul\u2019s army, had already
        gone to Mahanaim with Saul\u2019s son Ishbosheth.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:8 '
        content: <b>Ishbosheth </b>is another name for Esh-baal.
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'There he proclaimed Ishbosheth king over Gilead, Jezreel, Ephraim,
        Benjamin, the land of the Ashurites, and all the rest of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Ishbosheth, Saul\u2019s son, was forty years old when he became king,
        and he ruled from Mahanaim for two years. Meanwhile, the people of Judah
        remained loyal to David. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: War between Israel and Judah'
      title: War between Israel and Judah
      number: 11
      content: 'David made Hebron his capital, and he ruled as king of Judah for
        seven and a half years.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "One day Abner led Ishbosheth\u2019s troops from Mahanaim to Gibeon. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "About the same time, Joab son of Zeruiah led David\u2019s troops
        out and met them at the pool of Gibeon. The two groups sat down there, facing
        each other from opposite sides of the pool.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then Abner suggested to Joab, \u201CLet\u2019s have a few of our
        warriors fight hand to hand here in front of us.\u201D\u201CAll right,\u201D
        Joab agreed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "So twelve men were chosen to fight from each side\u2014twelve men
        of Benjamin representing Ishbosheth son of Saul, and twelve representing
        David. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Each one grabbed his opponent by the hair and thrust his sword into
        the other\u2019s side so that all of them died. So this place at Gibeon has
        been known ever since as the Field of Swords.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Helkath-hazzurim.</b>
    - name: '17: The Death of Asahel'
      title: The Death of Asahel
      number: 17
      content: 'A fierce battle followed that day, and Abner and the men of Israel
        were defeated by the forces of David.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Joab, Abishai, and Asahel\u2014the three sons of Zeruiah\u2014were
        among David\u2019s forces that day. Asahel could run like a gazelle, "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'and he began chasing Abner. He pursued him relentlessly, not stopping
        for anything. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When Abner looked back and saw him coming, he called out, \u201CIs
        that you, Asahel?\u201D\u201CYes, it is,\u201D he replied.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CGo fight someone else!\u201D Abner warned. \u201CTake on one
        of the younger men, and strip him of his weapons.\u201D But Asahel kept right
        on chasing Abner.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Again Abner shouted to him, \u201CGet away from here! I don\u2019t
        want to kill you. How could I ever face your brother Joab again?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "But Asahel refused to turn back, so Abner thrust the butt end of
        his spear through Asahel\u2019s stomach, and the spear came out through his
        back. He stumbled to the ground and died there. And everyone who came by
        that spot stopped and stood still when they saw Asahel lying there.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'When Joab and Abishai found out what had happened, they set out after
        Abner. The sun was just going down as they arrived at the hill of Ammah near
        Giah, along the road to the wilderness of Gibeon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Abner\u2019s troops from the tribe of Benjamin regrouped there at
        the top of the hill to take a stand.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Abner shouted down to Joab, \u201CMust we always be killing each
        other? Don\u2019t you realize that bitterness is the only result? When will
        you call off your men from chasing their Israelite brothers?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Then Joab said, \u201CGod only knows what would have happened if
        you hadn\u2019t spoken, for we would have chased you all night if necessary.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "So Joab blew the ram\u2019s horn, and his men stopped chasing the
        troops of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "All that night Abner and his men retreated through the Jordan Valley.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        They crossed the Jordan River, traveling all through the morning,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        and didn\u2019t stop until they arrived at Mahanaim.  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:29a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Arabah.</b>
      - number: '2:29b '
        content: Or <b>continued on through the Bithron. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew
          is uncertain.
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Meanwhile, Joab and his men also returned home. When Joab counted
        his casualties, he discovered that only 19 men were missing in addition to
        Asahel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "But 360 of Abner\u2019s men had been killed, all from the tribe of
        Benjamin. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Joab and his men took Asahel\u2019s body to Bethlehem and buried
        him there in his father\u2019s tomb. Then they traveled all night and reached
        Hebron at daybreak."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: David\u2019s Sons Born in Hebron"
      title: "David\u2019s Sons Born in Hebron"
      number: 1
      content: "  That was the beginning of a long war between those who were loyal
        to Saul and those loyal to David. As time passed David became stronger and
        stronger, while Saul\u2019s dynasty became weaker and weaker.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'These are the sons who were born to David in Hebron:The oldest was
        Amnon, whose mother was Ahinoam from Jezreel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The second was Daniel,[[COMMENT(0)]] whose mother was Abigail, the
        widow of Nabal from Carmel.The third was Absalom, whose mother was Maacah,
        the daughter of Talmai, king of Geshur.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:3 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 3:1 (see also Greek version, which
          reads <b>Daluia, </b>and possible support by Dead Sea Scrolls); Hebrew
          reads <b>Kileab.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The fourth was Adonijah, whose mother was Haggith.The fifth was Shephatiah,
        whose mother was Abital.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: Abner Joins Forces with David'
      title: Abner Joins Forces with David
      number: 5
      content: "The sixth was Ithream, whose mother was Eglah, David\u2019s wife.These
        sons were all born to David in Hebron.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'As the war between the house of Saul and the house of David went
        on, Abner became a powerful leader among those loyal to Saul. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "One day Ishbosheth,[[COMMENT(0)]] Saul\u2019s son, accused Abner
        of sleeping with one of his father\u2019s concubines, a woman named Rizpah,
        daughter of Aiah.  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:7 '
        content: <b>Ishbosheth </b>is another name for Esh-baal.
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Abner was furious. \u201CAm I some Judean dog to be kicked around
        like this?\u201D he shouted. \u201CAfter all I have done for your father,
        Saul, and his family and friends by not handing you over to David, is this
        my reward\u2014that you find fault with me about this woman? "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "May God strike me and even kill me if I don\u2019t do everything
        I can to help David get what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has promised
        him! "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "I\u2019m going to take Saul\u2019s kingdom and give it to David.
        I will establish the throne of David over Israel as well as Judah, all the
        way from Dan in the north to Beersheba in the south.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Ishbosheth didn\u2019t dare say another word because he was afraid
        of what Abner might do.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then Abner sent messengers to David, saying, \u201CDoesn\u2019t the
        entire land belong to you? Make a solemn pact with me, and I will help turn
        over all of Israel to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D David replied, \u201Cbut I will not negotiate
        with you unless you bring back my wife Michal, Saul\u2019s daughter, when
        you come.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "David then sent this message to Ishbosheth, Saul\u2019s son: \u201CGive
        me back my wife Michal, for I bought her with the lives[[COMMENT(0)]] of
        100 Philistines.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the foreskins.</b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So Ishbosheth took Michal away from her husband, Palti[[COMMENT(0)]]
        son of Laish. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:15 '
        content: As in 1 Sam 25:44; Hebrew reads <b>Paltiel, </b>a variant spelling
          of Palti.
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Palti followed along behind her as far as Bahurim, weeping as he
        went. Then Abner told him, \u201CGo back home!\u201D So Palti returned.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Meanwhile, Abner had consulted with the elders of Israel. \u201CFor
        some time now,\u201D he told them, \u201Cyou have wanted to make David your
        king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Now is the time! For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has said, \u2018I
        have chosen David to save my people Israel from the hands of the Philistines
        and from all their other enemies.\u2019\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Abner also spoke with the men of Benjamin. Then he went to Hebron
        to tell David that all the people of Israel and Benjamin had agreed to support
        him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'When Abner and twenty of his men came to Hebron, David entertained
        them with a great feast. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: Joab Murders Abner'
      title: Joab Murders Abner
      number: 21
      content: "Then Abner said to David, \u201CLet me go and call an assembly of
        all Israel to support my lord the king. They will make a covenant with you
        to make you their king, and you will rule over everything your heart desires.\u201D
        So David sent Abner safely on his way.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "But just after David had sent Abner away in safety, Joab and some
        of David\u2019s troops returned from a raid, bringing much plunder with them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'When Joab arrived, he was told that Abner had just been there visiting
        the king and had been sent away in safety.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Joab rushed to the king and demanded, \u201CWhat have you done? What
        do you mean by letting Abner get away? "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "You know perfectly well that he came to spy on you and find out everything
        you\u2019re doing!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Joab then left David and sent messengers to catch up with Abner,
        asking him to return. They found him at the well of Sirah and brought him
        back, though David knew nothing about it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When Abner arrived back at Hebron, Joab took him aside at the gateway
        as if to speak with him privately. But then he stabbed Abner in the stomach
        and killed him in revenge for killing his brother Asahel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "When David heard about it, he declared, \u201CI vow by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        that I and my kingdom are forever innocent of this crime against Abner son
        of Ner. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Joab and his family are the guilty ones. May the family of Joab be
        cursed in every generation with a man who has open sores or leprosy[[COMMENT(0)]]
        or who walks on crutches[[COMMENT(1)]] or dies by the sword or begs for food!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:29a '
        content: Or <b>or a contagious skin disease. </b>The Hebrew word used here
          can describe various skin diseases.
      - number: '3:29b '
        content: Or <b>who is effeminate; </b>Hebrew reads <b>who handles a spindle.</b>
    - name: "30: David Mourns Abner\u2019s Death"
      title: "David Mourns Abner\u2019s Death"
      number: 30
      content: 'So Joab and his brother Abishai killed Abner because Abner had killed
        their brother Asahel at the battle of Gibeon.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then David said to Joab and all those who were with him, \u201CTear
        your clothes and put on burlap. Mourn for Abner.\u201D And King David himself
        walked behind the procession to the grave. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'They buried Abner in Hebron, and the king and all the people wept
        at his graveside. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Then the king sang this funeral song for Abner:\u201CShould Abner
        have died as fools die?  "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Your hands were not bound;your feet were not chained.No, you were
        murdered\u2014the victim of a wicked plot.\u201DAll the people wept again
        for Abner. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "David had refused to eat anything on the day of the funeral, and
        now everyone begged him to eat. But David had made a vow, saying, \u201CMay
        God strike me and even kill me if I eat anything before sundown.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'This pleased the people very much. In fact, everything the king did
        pleased them! '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "So everyone in Judah and all Israel understood that David was not
        responsible for Abner\u2019s murder.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Then King David said to his officials, \u201CDon\u2019t you realize
        that a great commander has fallen today in Israel? "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "And even though I am the anointed king, these two sons of Zeruiah\u2014Joab
        and Abishai\u2014are too strong for me to control. So may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        repay these evil men for their evil deeds.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Murder of Ishbosheth'
      title: The Murder of Ishbosheth
      number: 1
      content: "  When Ishbosheth,[[COMMENT(0)]] Saul\u2019s son, heard about Abner\u2019s
        death at Hebron, he lost all courage, and all Israel became paralyzed with
        fear. "
      comments:
      - number: '4:1 '
        content: <b>Ishbosheth </b>is another name for Esh-baal.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Now there were two brothers, Baanah and Recab, who were captains
        of Ishbosheth\u2019s raiding parties. They were sons of Rimmon, a member
        of the tribe of Benjamin who lived in Beeroth. The town of Beeroth is now
        part of Benjamin\u2019s territory "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'because the original people of Beeroth fled to Gittaim, where they
        still live as foreigners.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "(Saul\u2019s son Jonathan had a son named Mephibosheth,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        who was crippled as a child. He was five years old when the report came from
        Jezreel that Saul and Jonathan had been killed in battle. When the child\u2019s
        nurse heard the news, she picked him up and fled. But as she hurried away,
        she dropped him, and he became crippled.)  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:4 '
        content: <b>Mephibosheth </b>is another name for Merib-baal.
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "One day Recab and Baanah, the sons of Rimmon from Beeroth, went to
        Ishbosheth\u2019s house around noon as he was taking his midday rest. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The doorkeeper, who had been sifting wheat, became drowsy and fell
        asleep. So Recab and Baanah slipped past her.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:6 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>So they went into the house
          pretending to fetch wheat, but they stabbed him in the stomach. Then Recab
          and Baanah escaped.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'They went into the house and found Ishbosheth sleeping on his bed.
        They struck and killed him and cut off his head. Then, taking his head with
        them, they fled across the Jordan Valley[[COMMENT(0)]] through the night. '
      comments:
      - number: '4:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Arabah.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "When they arrived at Hebron, they presented Ishbosheth\u2019s head
        to David. \u201CLook!\u201D they exclaimed to the king. \u201CHere is the
        head of Ishbosheth, the son of your enemy Saul who tried to kill you. Today
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has given my lord the king revenge on Saul
        and his entire family!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "But David said to Recab and Baanah, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who saves me from all my enemies, is my witness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Someone once told me, \u2018Saul is dead,\u2019 thinking he was bringing
        me good news. But I seized him and killed him at Ziklag. That\u2019s the
        reward I gave him for his news! "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "How much more should I reward evil men who have killed an innocent
        man in his own house and on his own bed? Shouldn\u2019t I hold you responsible
        for his blood and rid the earth of you?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "So David ordered his young men to kill them, and they did. They cut
        off their hands and feet and hung their bodies beside the pool in Hebron.
        Then they took Ishbosheth\u2019s head and buried it in Abner\u2019s tomb
        in Hebron."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David Becomes King of All Israel'
      title: David Becomes King of All Israel
      number: 1
      content: "  Then all the tribes of Israel went to David at Hebron and told
        him, \u201CWe are your own flesh and blood. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "In the past,[[COMMENT(0)]] when Saul was our king, you were the one
        who really led the forces of Israel. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told you, \u2018You will be the shepherd of my people Israel. You will be
        Israel\u2019s leader.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:2 '
        content: Or <b>For some time.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So there at Hebron, King David made a covenant before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with all the elders of Israel. And they anointed him king of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'David was thirty years old when he began to reign, and he reigned
        forty years in all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: David Captures Jerusalem'
      title: David Captures Jerusalem
      number: 5
      content: 'He had reigned over Judah from Hebron for seven years and six months,
        and from Jerusalem he reigned over all Israel and Judah for thirty-three
        years.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "David then led his men to Jerusalem to fight against the Jebusites,
        the original inhabitants of the land who were living there. The Jebusites
        taunted David, saying, \u201CYou\u2019ll never get in here! Even the blind
        and lame could keep you out!\u201D For the Jebusites thought they were safe. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'But David captured the fortress of Zion, which is now called the
        City of David.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "On the day of the attack, David said to his troops, \u201CI hate
        those \u2018lame\u2019 and \u2018blind\u2019 Jebusites.[[COMMENT(0)]] Whoever
        attacks them should strike by going into the city through the water tunnel.[[COMMENT(1)]]\u201D
        That is the origin of the saying, \u201CThe blind and the lame may not enter
        the house.\u201D[[COMMENT(2)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:8a '
        content: "Or <b>Those \u2018lame\u2019 and \u2018blind\u2019 Jebusites hate
          me.</b>"
      - number: '5:8b '
        content: Or <b>with scaling hooks. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
      - number: '5:8c '
        content: The meaning of this saying is uncertain.
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'So David made the fortress his home, and he called it the City of
        David. He extended the city, starting at the supporting terraces[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and working inward. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the millo. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "And David became more and more powerful, because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God of Heaven\u2019s Armies was with him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Then King Hiram of Tyre sent messengers to David, along with cedar
        timber and carpenters and stonemasons, and they built David a palace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'And David realized that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had confirmed
        him as king over Israel and had blessed his kingdom for the sake of his people
        Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'After moving from Hebron to Jerusalem, David married more concubines
        and wives, and they had more sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "These are the names of David\u2019s sons who were born in Jerusalem:
        Shammua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon, "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Ibhar, Elishua, Nepheg, Japhia, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: David Conquers the Philistines'
      title: David Conquers the Philistines
      number: 16
      content: 'Elishama, Eliada, and Eliphelet.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'When the Philistines heard that David had been anointed king of Israel,
        they mobilized all their forces to capture him. But David was told they were
        coming, so he went into the stronghold. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The Philistines arrived and spread out across the valley of Rephaim. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "So David asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CShould I go
        out to fight the Philistines? Will you hand them over to me?\u201DThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        replied to David, \u201CYes, go ahead. I will certainly hand them over to
        you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "So David went to Baal-perazim and defeated the Philistines there.
        \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did it!\u201D David exclaimed. \u201CHe
        burst through my enemies like a raging flood!\u201D So he named that place
        Baal-perazim (which means \u201Cthe Lord who bursts through\u201D). "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The Philistines had abandoned their idols there, so David and his
        men confiscated them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'But after a while the Philistines returned and again spread out across
        the valley of Rephaim. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "And again David asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> what to do.
        \u201CDo not attack them straight on,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        replied. \u201CInstead, circle around behind and attack them near the poplar[[COMMENT(0)]]
        trees. "
      comments:
      - number: '5:23 '
        content: Or <b>aspen, </b>or <b>balsam; </b>also in 5:24. The exact identification
          of this tree is uncertain.
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "When you hear a sound like marching feet in the tops of the poplar
        trees, be on the alert! That will be the signal that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is moving ahead of you to strike down the Philistine army.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: So David did what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded, and he
        struck down the Philistines all the way from Gibeon[[COMMENT(0)]] to Gezer.
      comments:
      - number: '5:25 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 1 Chr 14:16); Hebrew reads <b>Geba.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Moving the Ark to Jerusalem'
      title: Moving the Ark to Jerusalem
      number: 1
      content: '  Then David again gathered all the elite troops in Israel, 30,000
        in all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He led them to Baalah of Judah[[COMMENT(0)]] to bring back the Ark
        of God, which bears the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s
        Armies,[[COMMENT(1)]]<smallcaps> who is enthroned between the cherubim. </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: '6:2a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Baale of Judah, </b>another name for Kiriath-jearim; compare
          1 Chr 13:6.
      - number: '6:2b '
        content: "Or <b>the Ark of God where the Name is proclaimed\u2014the name
          of the <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span> of Heaven\u2019s
          Armies.</b>"
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "They placed the Ark of God on a new cart and brought it from Abinadab\u2019s
        house, which was on a hill. Uzzah and Ahio, Abinadab\u2019s sons, were guiding
        the cart "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'that carried the Ark of God.[[COMMENT(0)]] Ahio walked in front of
        the Ark. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:4 '
        content: "As in Dead Sea Scrolls and some Greek manuscripts; Masoretic Text
          reads <b>and they brought it from Abinadab\u2019s house, which was on a
          hill, with the Ark of God.</b>"
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "David and all the people of Israel were celebrating before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        singing songs[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> and playing all kinds of musical instruments\u2014lyres,
        harps, tambourines, castanets, and cymbals.</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:5 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version (see also 1 Chr 13:8);
          Masoretic Text reads <b>before the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>
          with all manner of cypress wood.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'But when they arrived at the threshing floor of Nacon, the oxen stumbled,
        and Uzzah reached out his hand and steadied the Ark of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anger was aroused against
        Uzzah, and God struck him dead because of this.[[COMMENT(0)]] So Uzzah died
        right there beside the Ark of God.  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:7 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls; Masoretic Text reads <b>because of his irreverence.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "David was angry because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anger
        had burst out against Uzzah. He named that place Perez-uzzah (which means
        \u201Cto burst out against Uzzah\u201D), as it is still called today.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "David was now afraid of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and he asked,
        \u201CHow can I ever bring the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> back
        into my care?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So David decided not to move the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        into the City of David. Instead, he took it to the house of Obed-edom of
        Gath. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "The Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> remained there in Obed-edom\u2019s
        house for three months, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> blessed Obed-edom
        and his entire household.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then King David was told, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has
        blessed Obed-edom\u2019s household and everything he has because of the Ark
        of God.\u201D So David went there and brought the Ark of God from the house
        of Obed-edom to the City of David with a great celebration. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'After the men who were carrying the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had gone six steps, David sacrificed a bull and a fattened calf. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'And David danced before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> with all
        his might, wearing a priestly garment.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a linen ephod.</b>
    - name: "15: Michal\u2019s Contempt for David"
      title: "Michal\u2019s Contempt for David"
      number: 15
      content: "So David and all the people of Israel brought up the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with shouts of joy and the blowing of rams\u2019 horns.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'But as the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> entered the City
        of David, Michal, the daughter of Saul, looked down from her window. When
        she saw King David leaping and dancing before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        she was filled with contempt for him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'They brought the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and set it
        in its place inside the special tent David had prepared for it. And David
        sacrificed burnt offerings and peace offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "When he had finished his sacrifices, David blessed the people in
        the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Then he gave to every Israelite man and woman in the crowd a loaf
        of bread, a cake of dates,[[COMMENT(0)]] and a cake of raisins. Then all
        the people returned to their homes.  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:19 '
        content: Or <b>a portion of meat. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When David returned home to bless his own family, Michal, the daughter
        of Saul, came out to meet him. She said in disgust, \u201CHow distinguished
        the king of Israel looked today, shamelessly exposing himself to the servant
        girls like any vulgar person might do!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "David retorted to Michal, \u201CI was dancing before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who chose me above your father and all his family! He appointed me as the
        leader of Israel, the people of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, so I celebrate
        before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Yes, and I am willing to look even more foolish than this, even to
        be humiliated in my own eyes! But those servant girls you mentioned will
        indeed think I am distinguished!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: So Michal, the daughter of Saul, remained childless throughout her
        entire life.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: The \u2019s Covenant Promise to David"
      title: "The \u2019s Covenant Promise to David"
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  When King David was settled in his palace
        and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given him rest from all the surrounding
        enemies, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "the king summoned Nathan the prophet. \u201CLook,\u201D David said,
        \u201CI am living in a beautiful cedar palace,[[COMMENT(0)]] but the Ark
        of God is out there in a tent!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a house of cedar.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Nathan replied to the king, \u201CGo ahead and do whatever you have
        in mind, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is with you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'But that same night the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Nathan,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CGo and tell my servant David, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has declared: Are you the one to build a house for me to live in? "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'I have never lived in a house, from the day I brought the Israelites
        out of Egypt until this very day. I have always moved from one place to another
        with a tent and a Tabernacle as my dwelling. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Yet no matter where I have gone with the Israelites, I have never
        once complained to Israel\u2019s tribal leaders, the shepherds of my people
        Israel. I have never asked them, \u201CWhy haven\u2019t you built me a beautiful
        cedar house?\u201D\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CNow go and say to my servant David, \u2018This is what the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies has declared: I took
        you from tending sheep in the pasture and selected you to be the leader of
        my people Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'I have been with you wherever you have gone, and I have destroyed
        all your enemies before your eyes. Now I will make your name as famous as
        anyone who has ever lived on the earth! '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "And I will provide a homeland for my people Israel, planting them
        in a secure place where they will never be disturbed. Evil nations won\u2019t
        oppress them as they\u2019ve done in the past, "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "starting from the time I appointed judges to rule my people Israel.
        And I will give you rest from all your enemies.\u201C\u2018Furthermore, the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> declares that he will make a house for you\u2014a
        dynasty of kings! "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'For when you die and are buried with your ancestors, I will raise
        up one of your descendants, your own offspring, and I will make his kingdom
        strong. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "He is the one who will build a house\u2014a temple\u2014for my name.
        And I will secure his royal throne forever. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I will be his father, and he will be my son. If he sins, I will correct
        and discipline him with the rod, like any father would do. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'But my favor will not be taken from him as I took it from Saul, whom
        I removed from your sight. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Your house and your kingdom will continue before me[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for all time, and your throne will be secure forever.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:16 '
        content: As in Greek version and some Hebrew manuscripts; Masoretic Text
          reads <b>before you.</b>
    - name: "17: David\u2019s Prayer of Thanks"
      title: "David\u2019s Prayer of Thanks"
      number: 17
      content: 'So Nathan went back to David and told him everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had said in this vision.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then King David went in and sat before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and prayed,\u201CWho am I, O Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and what
        is my family, that you have brought me this far? "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: And now, Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, in addition to everything
        else, you speak of giving your servant a lasting dynasty! Do you deal with
        everyone this way, O Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '7:19 '
        content: Or <b>This is your instruction for all humanity, O Sovereign <span
          class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CWhat more can I say to you? You know what your servant is really
        like, Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Because of your promise and according to your will, you have done
        all these great things and have made them known to your servant.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CHow great you are, O Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!
        There is no one like you. We have never even heard of another God like you! "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'What other nation on earth is like your people Israel? What other
        nation, O God, have you redeemed from slavery to be your own people? You
        made a great name for yourself when you redeemed your people from Egypt.
        You performed awesome miracles and drove out the nations and gods that stood
        in their way.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:23 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 1 Chr 17:21); Hebrew reads <b>You
          made a name for yourself and awesome miracles for your land in the sight
          of your people, whom you redeemed from Egypt, the nations and their gods.</b>
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'You made Israel your very own people forever, and you, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        became their God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CAnd now, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God, I am your servant;
        do as you have promised concerning me and my family. Confirm it as a promise
        that will last forever. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "And may your name be honored forever so that everyone will say, \u2018The
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies is God over Israel!\u2019
        And may the house of your servant David continue before you forever.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies, God
        of Israel, I have been bold enough to pray this prayer to you because you
        have revealed all this to your servant, saying, \u2018I will build a house
        for you\u2014a dynasty of kings!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'For you are God, O Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Your words
        are truth, and you have promised these good things to your servant. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "And now, may it please you to bless the house of your servant, so
        that it may continue forever before you. For you have spoken, and when you
        grant a blessing to your servant, O Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        it is an eternal blessing!\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: David\u2019s Military Victories"
      title: "David\u2019s Military Victories"
      number: 1
      content: '  After this, David defeated and subdued the Philistines by conquering
        Gath, their largest town.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:1 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>by conquering Metheg-ammah, </b>a name that means \u201Cthe
          bridle,\u201D possibly referring to the size of the town or the tribute
          money taken from it. Compare 1 Chr 18:1."
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "David also conquered the land of Moab. He made the people lie down
        on the ground in a row, and he measured them off in groups with a length
        of rope. He measured off two groups to be executed for every one group to
        be spared. The Moabites who were spared became David\u2019s subjects and
        paid him tribute money.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'David also destroyed the forces of Hadadezer son of Rehob, king of
        Zobah, when Hadadezer marched out to strengthen his control along the Euphrates
        River. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'David captured 1,000 chariots, 7,000 charioteers,[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        20,000 foot soldiers. He crippled all the chariot horses except enough for
        100 chariots.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:4 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version (see also 1 Chr 18:4);
          Masoretic Text reads <b>captured 1,700 charioteers.</b>
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'When Arameans from Damascus arrived to help King Hadadezer, David
        killed 22,000 of them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then he placed several army garrisons in Damascus, the Aramean capital,
        and the Arameans became David\u2019s subjects and paid him tribute money.
        So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made David victorious wherever he went.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "David brought the gold shields of Hadadezer\u2019s officers to Jerusalem, "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "along with a large amount of bronze from Hadadezer\u2019s towns of
        Tebah[[COMMENT(0)]] and Berothai.  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:8 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Chr 18:8); Hebrew reads
          <b>Betah.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'When King Toi of Hamath heard that David had destroyed the entire
        army of Hadadezer, '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'he sent his son Joram to congratulate King David for his successful
        campaign. Hadadezer and Toi had been enemies and were often at war. Joram
        presented David with many gifts of silver, gold, and bronze.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "King David dedicated all these gifts to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        as he did with the silver and gold from the other nations he had defeated\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "from Edom,[[COMMENT(0)]] Moab, Ammon, Philistia, and Amalek\u2014and
        from Hadadezer son of Rehob, king of Zobah.  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:12 '
        content: As in a few Hebrew manuscripts and Greek and Syriac versions (see
          also 8:14; 1 Chr 18:11); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>Aram.</b>
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'So David became even more famous when he returned from destroying
        18,000 Edomites[[COMMENT(0)]] in the Valley of Salt. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:13 '
        content: As in a few Hebrew manuscripts and Greek and Syriac versions (see
          also 8:14; 1 Chr 18:12); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>Arameans.</b>
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "He placed army garrisons throughout Edom, and all the Edomites became
        David\u2019s subjects. In fact, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made David
        victorious wherever he went.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So David reigned over all Israel and did what was just and right
        for all his people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Joab son of Zeruiah was commander of the army. Jehoshaphat son of
        Ahilud was the royal historian. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Zadok son of Ahitub and Ahimelech son of Abiathar were the priests.
        Seraiah was the court secretary. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Benaiah son of Jehoiada was captain of the king\u2019s bodyguard.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        And David\u2019s sons served as priestly leaders.[[COMMENT(1)]]"
      comments:
      - number: '8:18a '
        content: Hebrew <b>of the Kerethites and Pelethites.</b>
      - number: '8:18b '
        content: "Hebrew <b>David\u2019s sons were priests; </b>compare parallel
          text at 1 Chr 18:17."
  - verses:
    - name: "1: David\u2019s Kindness to Mephibosheth"
      title: "David\u2019s Kindness to Mephibosheth"
      number: 1
      content: "  One day David asked, \u201CIs anyone in Saul\u2019s family still
        alive\u2014anyone to whom I can show kindness for Jonathan\u2019s sake?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He summoned a man named Ziba, who had been one of Saul\u2019s servants.
        \u201CAre you Ziba?\u201D the king asked.\u201CYes sir, I am,\u201D Ziba
        replied.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "The king then asked him, \u201CIs anyone still alive from Saul\u2019s
        family? If so, I want to show God\u2019s kindness to them.\u201DZiba replied,
        \u201CYes, one of Jonathan\u2019s sons is still alive. He is crippled in
        both feet.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CWhere is he?\u201D the king asked.\u201CIn Lo-debar,\u201D
        Ziba told him, \u201Cat the home of Makir son of Ammiel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So David sent for him and brought him from Makir\u2019s home. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "His name was Mephibosheth[[COMMENT(0)]]; he was Jonathan\u2019s son
        and Saul\u2019s grandson. When he came to David, he bowed low to the ground
        in deep respect. David said, \u201CGreetings, Mephibosheth.\u201DMephibosheth
        replied, \u201CI am your servant.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:6 '
        content: <b>Mephibosheth </b>is another name for Merib-baal.
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be afraid!\u201D David said. \u201CI intend to show
        kindness to you because of my promise to your father, Jonathan. I will give
        you all the property that once belonged to your grandfather Saul, and you
        will eat here with me at the king\u2019s table!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Mephibosheth bowed respectfully and exclaimed, \u201CWho is your
        servant, that you should show such kindness to a dead dog like me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then the king summoned Saul\u2019s servant Ziba and said, \u201CI
        have given your master\u2019s grandson everything that belonged to Saul and
        his family. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "You and your sons and servants are to farm the land for him to produce
        food for your master\u2019s household.[[COMMENT(0)]] But Mephibosheth, your
        master\u2019s grandson, will eat here at my table.\u201D (Ziba had fifteen
        sons and twenty servants.)  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:10 '
        content: "As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>your master\u2019s grandson.</b>"
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Ziba replied, \u201CYes, my lord the king; I am your servant, and
        I will do all that you have commanded.\u201D And from that time on, Mephibosheth
        ate regularly at David\u2019s table,[[COMMENT(0)]] like one of the king\u2019s
        own sons.  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:11 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>my table.</b>
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Mephibosheth had a young son named Mica. From then on, all the members
        of Ziba\u2019s household were Mephibosheth\u2019s servants. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And Mephibosheth, who was crippled in both feet, lived in Jerusalem
        and ate regularly at the king\u2019s table."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David Defeats the Ammonites'
      title: David Defeats the Ammonites
      number: 1
      content: '  Some time after this, King Nahash[[COMMENT(0)]] of the Ammonites
        died, and his son Hanun became king. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 19:1; Hebrew reads <b>the king.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "David said, \u201CI am going to show loyalty to Hanun just as his
        father, Nahash, was always loyal to me.\u201D So David sent ambassadors to
        express sympathy to Hanun about his father\u2019s death.But when David\u2019s
        ambassadors arrived in the land of Ammon, "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "the Ammonite commanders said to Hanun, their master, \u201CDo you
        really think these men are coming here to honor your father? No! David has
        sent them to spy out the city so they can come in and conquer it!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "So Hanun seized David\u2019s ambassadors and shaved off half of each
        man\u2019s beard, cut off their robes at the buttocks, and sent them back
        to David in shame.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When David heard what had happened, he sent messengers to tell the
        men, \u201CStay at Jericho until your beards grow out, and then come back.\u201D
        For they felt deep shame because of their appearance.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When the people of Ammon realized how seriously they had angered
        David, they sent and hired 20,000 Aramean foot soldiers from the lands of
        Beth-rehob and Zobah, 1,000 from the king of Maacah, and 12,000 from the
        land of Tob. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'When David heard about this, he sent Joab and all his warriors to
        fight them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The Ammonite troops came out and drew up their battle lines at the
        entrance of the city gate, while the Arameans from Zobah and Rehob and the
        men from Tob and Maacah positioned themselves to fight in the open fields.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "When Joab saw that he would have to fight on both the front and the
        rear, he chose some of Israel\u2019s elite troops and placed them under his
        personal command to fight the Arameans in the fields. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He left the rest of the army under the command of his brother Abishai,
        who was to attack the Ammonites. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CIf the Arameans are too strong for me, then come over and help
        me,\u201D Joab told his brother. \u201CAnd if the Ammonites are too strong
        for you, I will come and help you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Be courageous! Let us fight bravely for our people and the cities
        of our God. May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s will be done.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When Joab and his troops attacked, the Arameans began to run away. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'And when the Ammonites saw the Arameans running, they ran from Abishai
        and retreated into the city. After the battle was over, Joab returned to
        Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The Arameans now realized that they were no match for Israel. So
        when they regrouped, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "they were joined by additional Aramean troops summoned by Hadadezer
        from the other side of the Euphrates River.[[COMMENT(0)]] These troops arrived
        at Helam under the command of Shobach, the commander of Hadadezer\u2019s
        forces.  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the river.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'When David heard what was happening, he mobilized all Israel, crossed
        the Jordan River, and led the army to Helam. The Arameans positioned themselves
        in battle formation and fought against David. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "But again the Arameans fled from the Israelites. This time David\u2019s
        forces killed 700 charioteers and 40,000 foot soldiers,[[COMMENT(0)]] including
        Shobach, the commander of their army. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:18 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Chr 19:18); Hebrew reads
          <b>charioteers.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: When all the kings allied with Hadadezer saw that they had been defeated
        by Israel, they surrendered to Israel and became their subjects. After that,
        the Arameans were afraid to help the Ammonites.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David and Bathsheba'
      title: David and Bathsheba
      number: 1
      content: '  In the spring of the year,[[COMMENT(0)]] when kings normally go
        out to war, David sent Joab and the Israelite army to fight the Ammonites.
        They destroyed the Ammonite army and laid siege to the city of Rabbah. However,
        David stayed behind in Jerusalem.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>At the turn of the year. </b>The first day of the year
          in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in March or April.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Late one afternoon, after his midday rest, David got out of bed and
        was walking on the roof of the palace. As he looked out over the city, he
        noticed a woman of unusual beauty taking a bath. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "He sent someone to find out who she was, and he was told, \u201CShe
        is Bathsheba, the daughter of Eliam and the wife of Uriah the Hittite.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Then David sent messengers to get her; and when she came to the palace,
        he slept with her. She had just completed the purification rites after having
        her menstrual period. Then she returned home. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Later, when Bathsheba discovered that she was pregnant, she sent
        David a message, saying, \u201CI\u2019m pregnant.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then David sent word to Joab: \u201CSend me Uriah the Hittite.\u201D
        So Joab sent him to David. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'When Uriah arrived, David asked him how Joab and the army were getting
        along and how the war was progressing. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Then he told Uriah, \u201CGo on home and relax.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D
        David even sent a gift to Uriah after he had left the palace. "
      comments:
      - number: '11:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>and wash your feet, </b>an expression that may also have
          a connotation of ritualistic washing.
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "But Uriah didn\u2019t go home. He slept that night at the palace
        entrance with the king\u2019s palace guard.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "When David heard that Uriah had not gone home, he summoned him and
        asked, \u201CWhat\u2019s the matter? Why didn\u2019t you go home last night
        after being away for so long?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Uriah replied, \u201CThe Ark and the armies of Israel and Judah are
        living in tents,[[COMMENT(0)]] and Joab and my master\u2019s men are camping
        in the open fields. How could I go home to wine and dine and sleep with my
        wife? I swear that I would never do such a thing.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:11 '
        content: Or <b>at Succoth.</b>
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CWell, stay here today,\u201D David told him, \u201Cand tomorrow
        you may return to the army.\u201D So Uriah stayed in Jerusalem that day and
        the next. "
      comments: []
    - name: "13: David Arranges for Uriah\u2019s Death"
      title: "David Arranges for Uriah\u2019s Death"
      number: 13
      content: "Then David invited him to dinner and got him drunk. But even then
        he couldn\u2019t get Uriah to go home to his wife. Again he slept at the
        palace entrance with the king\u2019s palace guard.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So the next morning David wrote a letter to Joab and gave it to Uriah
        to deliver. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The letter instructed Joab, \u201CStation Uriah on the front lines
        where the battle is fiercest. Then pull back so that he will be killed.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So Joab assigned Uriah to a spot close to the city wall where he
        knew the enemy\u2019s strongest men were fighting. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'And when the enemy soldiers came out of the city to fight, Uriah
        the Hittite was killed along with several other Israelite soldiers.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Then Joab sent a battle report to David. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "He told his messenger, \u201CReport all the news of the battle to
        the king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "But he might get angry and ask, \u2018Why did the troops go so close
        to the city? Didn\u2019t they know there would be shooting from the walls? "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Wasn\u2019t Abimelech son of Gideon[[COMMENT(0)]] killed at Thebez
        by a woman who threw a millstone down on him from the wall? Why would you
        get so close to the wall?\u2019 Then tell him, \u2018Uriah the Hittite was
        killed, too.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>son of Jerub-besheth. </b>Jerub-besheth is a variation
          on the name Jerub-baal, which is another name for Gideon; see Judg 6:32.
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So the messenger went to Jerusalem and gave a complete report to
        David. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CThe enemy came out against us in the open fields,\u201D he
        said. \u201CAnd as we chased them back to the city gate, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "the archers on the wall shot arrows at us. Some of the king\u2019s
        men were killed, including Uriah the Hittite.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CWell, tell Joab not to be discouraged,\u201D David said. \u201CThe
        sword devours this one today and that one tomorrow! Fight harder next time,
        and conquer the city!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "When Uriah\u2019s wife heard that her husband was dead, she mourned
        for him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: When the period of mourning was over, David sent for her and brought
        her to the palace, and she became one of his wives. Then she gave birth to
        a son. But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was displeased with what David
        had done.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Nathan Rebukes David'
      title: Nathan Rebukes David
      number: 1
      content: "  So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent Nathan the prophet to tell
        David this story: \u201CThere were two men in a certain town. One was rich,
        and one was poor. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The rich man owned a great many sheep and cattle. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "The poor man owned nothing but one little lamb he had bought. He
        raised that little lamb, and it grew up with his children. It ate from the
        man\u2019s own plate and drank from his cup. He cuddled it in his arms like
        a baby daughter. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "One day a guest arrived at the home of the rich man. But instead
        of killing an animal from his own flock or herd, he took the poor man\u2019s
        lamb and killed it and prepared it for his guest.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "David was furious. \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives,\u201D he vowed, \u201Cany man who would do such a thing deserves to
        die! "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "He must repay four lambs to the poor man for the one he stole and
        for having no pity.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then Nathan said to David, \u201CYou are that man! The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, says: I anointed you king of Israel and saved you from
        the power of Saul. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "I gave you your master\u2019s house and his wives and the kingdoms
        of Israel and Judah. And if that had not been enough, I would have given
        you much, much more. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Why, then, have you despised the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and done this horrible deed? For you have murdered Uriah the Hittite with
        the sword of the Ammonites and stolen his wife. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "From this time on, your family will live by the sword because you
        have despised me by taking Uriah\u2019s wife to be your own.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Because
        of what you have done, I will cause your own household to rebel against you.
        I will give your wives to another man before your very eyes, and he will
        go to bed with them in public view. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: David Confesses His Guilt'
      title: David Confesses His Guilt
      number: 12
      content: "You did it secretly, but I will make this happen to you openly in
        the sight of all Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then David confessed to Nathan, \u201CI have sinned against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201DNathan
        replied, \u201CYes, but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has forgiven you,
        and you won\u2019t die for this sin. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Nevertheless, because you have shown utter contempt for the word
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> by doing this,
        your child will die.\u201D</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '12:14 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls; Masoretic Text reads <b>the enemies of the
          <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord.</span></b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "After Nathan returned to his home, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        sent a deadly illness to the child of David and Uriah\u2019s wife. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'David begged God to spare the child. He went without food and lay
        all night on the bare ground. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The elders of his household pleaded with him to get up and eat with
        them, but he refused.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then on the seventh day the child died. David\u2019s advisers were
        afraid to tell him. \u201CHe wouldn\u2019t listen to reason while the child
        was ill,\u201D they said. \u201CWhat drastic thing will he do when we tell
        him the child is dead?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "When David saw them whispering, he realized what had happened. \u201CIs
        the child dead?\u201D he asked.\u201CYes,\u201D they replied, \u201Che is
        dead.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Then David got up from the ground, washed himself, put on lotions,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and changed his clothes. He went to the Tabernacle and worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        After that, he returned to the palace and was served food and ate.  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>anointed himself.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "His advisers were amazed. \u201CWe don\u2019t understand you,\u201D
        they told him. \u201CWhile the child was still living, you wept and refused
        to eat. But now that the child is dead, you have stopped your mourning and
        are eating again.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "David replied, \u201CI fasted and wept while the child was alive,
        for I said, \u2018Perhaps the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will be gracious
        to me and let the child live.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "But why should I fast when he is dead? Can I bring him back again?
        I will go to him one day, but he cannot return to me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Then David comforted Bathsheba, his wife, and slept with her. She
        became pregnant and gave birth to a son, and David[[COMMENT(0)]] named him
        Solomon. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> loved the child '
      comments:
      - number: '12:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>he; </b>an alternate Hebrew reading and some Hebrew manuscripts
          read <b>she.</b>
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "and sent word through Nathan the prophet that they should name him
        Jedidiah (which means \u201Cbeloved of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u201D),
        as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>David
        Captures Rabbah</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '12:25 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>because of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Meanwhile, Joab was fighting against Rabbah, the capital of Ammon,
        and he captured the royal fortifications.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:26 '
        content: Or <b>the royal city.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Joab sent messengers to tell David, \u201CI have fought against Rabbah
        and captured its water supply.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '12:27 '
        content: Or <b>captured the city of water.</b>
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Now bring the rest of the army and capture the city. Otherwise, I
        will capture it and get credit for the victory.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'So David gathered the rest of the army and went to Rabbah, and he
        fought against it and captured it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "David removed the crown from the king\u2019s head,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and it was placed on his own head. The crown was made of gold and set with
        gems, and it weighed seventy-five pounds.[[COMMENT(1)]] David took a vast
        amount of plunder from the city. "
      comments:
      - number: '12:30a '
        content: Or <b>from the head of Milcom </b>(as in Greek version). Milcom,
          also called Molech, was the god of the Ammonites.
      - number: '12:30b '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 talent </b>[34 kilograms].
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: He also made slaves of the people of Rabbah and forced them to labor
        with[[COMMENT(0)]] saws, iron picks, and iron axes, and to work in the brick
        kilns.[[COMMENT(1)]] That is how he dealt with the people of all the Ammonite
        towns. Then David and all the army returned to Jerusalem.
      comments:
      - number: '12:31a '
        content: Hebrew <b>He also brought out the people [of Rabbah] and put them
          under.</b>
      - number: '12:31b '
        content: Hebrew <b>and he made them pass through the brick kilns.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Rape of Tamar'
      title: The Rape of Tamar
      number: 1
      content: "  Now David\u2019s son Absalom had a beautiful sister named Tamar.
        And Amnon, her half brother, fell desperately in love with her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Amnon became so obsessed with Tamar that he became ill. She was a
        virgin, and Amnon thought he could never have her.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "But Amnon had a very crafty friend\u2014his cousin Jonadab. He was
        the son of David\u2019s brother Shimea.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shimeah </b>(also in 13:32), a variant spelling of Shimea;
          compare 1 Chr 2:13.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "One day Jonadab said to Amnon, \u201CWhat\u2019s the trouble? Why
        should the son of a king look so dejected morning after morning?\u201DSo
        Amnon told him, \u201CI am in love with Tamar, my brother Absalom\u2019s
        sister.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CWell,\u201D Jonadab said, \u201CI\u2019ll tell you what to
        do. Go back to bed and pretend you are ill. When your father comes to see
        you, ask him to let Tamar come and prepare some food for you. Tell him you\u2019ll
        feel better if she prepares it as you watch and feeds you with her own hands.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So Amnon lay down and pretended to be sick. And when the king came
        to see him, Amnon asked him, \u201CPlease let my sister Tamar come and cook
        my favorite dish[[COMMENT(0)]] as I watch. Then I can eat it from her own
        hands.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '13:6 '
        content: Or <b>a couple of cakes; </b>also in 13:8, 10.
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "So David agreed and sent Tamar to Amnon\u2019s house to prepare some
        food for him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "When Tamar arrived at Amnon\u2019s house, she went to the place where
        he was lying down so he could watch her mix some dough. Then she baked his
        favorite dish for him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "But when she set the serving tray before him, he refused to eat.
        \u201CEveryone get out of here,\u201D Amnon told his servants. So they all
        left.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Then he said to Tamar, \u201CNow bring the food into my bedroom and
        feed it to me here.\u201D So Tamar took his favorite dish to him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "But as she was feeding him, he grabbed her and demanded, \u201CCome
        to bed with me, my darling sister.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CNo, my brother!\u201D she cried. \u201CDon\u2019t be foolish!
        Don\u2019t do this to me! Such wicked things aren\u2019t done in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Where could I go in my shame? And you would be called one of the
        greatest fools in Israel. Please, just speak to the king about it, and he
        will let you marry me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "But Amnon wouldn\u2019t listen to her, and since he was stronger
        than she was, he raped her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Then suddenly Amnon\u2019s love turned to hate, and he hated her
        even more than he had loved her. \u201CGet out of here!\u201D he snarled
        at her.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CNo, no!\u201D Tamar cried. \u201CSending me away now is worse
        than what you\u2019ve already done to me.\u201DBut Amnon wouldn\u2019t listen
        to her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "He shouted for his servant and demanded, \u201CThrow this woman out,
        and lock the door behind her!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "So the servant put her out and locked the door behind her. She was
        wearing a long, beautiful robe,[[COMMENT(0)]] as was the custom in those
        days for the king\u2019s virgin daughters. "
      comments:
      - number: '13:18 '
        content: Or <b>a robe with sleeves, </b>or <b>an ornamented robe. </b>The
          meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'But now Tamar tore her robe and put ashes on her head. And then,
        with her face in her hands, she went away crying.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Her brother Absalom saw her and asked, \u201CIs it true that Amnon
        has been with you? Well, my sister, keep quiet for now, since he\u2019s your
        brother. Don\u2019t you worry about it.\u201D So Tamar lived as a desolate
        woman in her brother Absalom\u2019s house.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'When King David heard what had happened, he was very angry.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '13:21 '
        content: Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version add <b>But he did not punish
          his son Amnon, because he loved him, for he was his firstborn.</b>
    - name: "22: Absalom\u2019s Revenge on Amnon"
      title: "Absalom\u2019s Revenge on Amnon"
      number: 22
      content: 'And though Absalom never spoke to Amnon about this, he hated Amnon
        deeply because of what he had done to his sister.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Two years later, when Absalom\u2019s sheep were being sheared at
        Baal-hazor near Ephraim, Absalom invited all the king\u2019s sons to come
        to a feast. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "He went to the king and said, \u201CMy sheep-shearers are now at
        work. Would the king and his servants please come to celebrate the occasion
        with me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "The king replied, \u201CNo, my son. If we all came, we would be too
        much of a burden on you.\u201D Absalom pressed him, but the king would not
        come, though he gave Absalom his blessing.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CWell, then,\u201D Absalom said, \u201Cif you can\u2019t come,
        how about sending my brother Amnon with us?\u201D\u201CWhy Amnon?\u201D the
        king asked. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'But Absalom kept on pressing the king until he finally agreed to
        let all his sons attend, including Amnon. So Absalom prepared a feast fit
        for a king.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '13:27 '
        content: As in Greek and Latin versions (compare also Dead Sea Scrolls);
          the Hebrew text lacks this sentence.
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Absalom told his men, \u201CWait until Amnon gets drunk; then at
        my signal, kill him! Don\u2019t be afraid. I\u2019m the one who has given
        the command. Take courage and do it!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "So at Absalom\u2019s signal they murdered Amnon. Then the other sons
        of the king jumped on their mules and fled.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "As they were on the way back to Jerusalem, this report reached David:
        \u201CAbsalom has killed all the king\u2019s sons; not one is left alive!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'The king got up, tore his robe, and threw himself on the ground.
        His advisers also tore their clothes in horror and sorrow.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "But just then Jonadab, the son of David\u2019s brother Shimea, arrived
        and said, \u201CNo, don\u2019t believe that all the king\u2019s sons have
        been killed! It was only Amnon! Absalom has been plotting this ever since
        Amnon raped his sister Tamar. "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "No, my lord the king, your sons aren\u2019t all dead! It was only
        Amnon.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Meanwhile Absalom escaped.Then the watchman on the Jerusalem wall
        saw a great crowd coming down the hill on the road from the west. He ran
        to tell the king, \u201CI see a crowd of people coming from the Horonaim
        road along the side of the hill.\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:34 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew lacks this sentence.
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "\u201CLook!\u201D Jonadab told the king. \u201CThere they are now!
        The king\u2019s sons are coming, just as I said.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'They soon arrived, weeping and sobbing, and the king and all his
        servants wept bitterly with them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'And David mourned many days for his son Amnon.Absalom fled to his
        grandfather, Talmai son of Ammihud, the king of Geshur. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'He stayed there in Geshur for three years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "And King David,[[COMMENT(0)]] now reconciled to Amnon\u2019s death,
        longed to be reunited with his son Absalom.[[COMMENT(1)]]"
      comments:
      - number: '13:39a '
        content: Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version read <b>And the spirit of the
          king.</b>
      - number: '13:39b '
        content: Or <b>no longer felt a need to go out after Absalom.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Joab Arranges for Absalom\u2019s Return"
      title: "Joab Arranges for Absalom\u2019s Return"
      number: 1
      content: '  Joab realized how much the king longed to see Absalom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So he sent for a woman from Tekoa who had a reputation for great
        wisdom. He said to her, \u201CPretend you are in mourning; wear mourning
        clothes and don\u2019t put on lotions.[[COMMENT(0)]] Act like a woman who
        has been mourning for the dead for a long time. "
      comments:
      - number: '14:2 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>don\u2019t anoint yourself with oil.</b>"
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then go to the king and tell him the story I am about to tell you.\u201D
        Then Joab told her what to say.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "When the woman from Tekoa approached[[COMMENT(0)]] the king, she
        bowed with her face to the ground in deep respect and cried out, \u201CO
        king! Help me!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:4 '
        content: As in many Hebrew manuscripts and Greek and Syriac versions; Masoretic
          Text reads <b>spoke to.</b>
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CWhat\u2019s the trouble?\u201D the king asked.\u201CAlas, I
        am a widow!\u201D she replied. \u201CMy husband is dead. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'My two sons had a fight out in the field. And since no one was there
        to stop it, one of them was killed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Now the rest of the family is demanding, \u2018Let us have your son.
        We will execute him for murdering his brother. He doesn\u2019t deserve to
        inherit his family\u2019s property.\u2019 They want to extinguish the only
        coal I have left, and my husband\u2019s name and family will disappear from
        the face of the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CLeave it to me,\u201D the king told her. \u201CGo home, and
        I\u2019ll see to it that no one touches him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201COh, thank you, my lord the king,\u201D the woman from Tekoa
        replied. \u201CIf you are criticized for helping me, let the blame fall on
        me and on my father\u2019s house, and let the king and his throne be innocent.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CIf anyone objects,\u201D the king said, \u201Cbring him to
        me. I can assure you he will never harm you again!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then she said, \u201CPlease swear to me by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God that you won\u2019t let anyone take vengeance against my son. I
        want no more bloodshed.\u201D\u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives,\u201D he replied, \u201Cnot a hair on your son\u2019s head will be
        disturbed!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CPlease allow me to ask one more thing of my lord the king,\u201D
        she said.\u201CGo ahead and speak,\u201D he responded.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "She replied, \u201CWhy don\u2019t you do as much for the people of
        God as you have promised to do for me? You have convicted yourself in making
        this decision, because you have refused to bring home your own banished son. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'All of us must die eventually. Our lives are like water spilled out
        on the ground, which cannot be gathered up again. But God does not just sweep
        life away; instead, he devises ways to bring us back when we have been separated
        from him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CI have come to plead with my lord the king because people have
        threatened me. I said to myself, \u2018Perhaps the king will listen to me "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'and rescue us from those who would cut us off from the inheritance[[COMMENT(0)]]
        God has given us. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:16 '
        content: Or <b>the property; </b>or <b>the people.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Yes, my lord the king will give us peace of mind again.\u2019 I know
        that you are like an angel of God in discerning good from evil. May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God be with you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CI must know one thing,\u201D the king replied, \u201Cand tell
        me the truth.\u201D\u201CYes, my lord the king,\u201D she responded.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CDid Joab put you up to this?\u201DAnd the woman replied, \u201CMy
        lord the king, how can I deny it? Nobody can hide anything from you. Yes,
        Joab sent me and told me what to say. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "He did it to place the matter before you in a different light. But
        you are as wise as an angel of God, and you understand everything that happens
        among us!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "So the king sent for Joab and told him, \u201CAll right, go and bring
        back the young man Absalom.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Joab bowed with his face to the ground in deep respect and said,
        \u201CAt last I know that I have gained your approval, my lord the king,
        for you have granted me this request!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Then Joab went to Geshur and brought Absalom back to Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: Absalom Reconciled to David'
      title: Absalom Reconciled to David
      number: 24
      content: "But the king gave this order: \u201CAbsalom may go to his own house,
        but he must never come into my presence.\u201D So Absalom did not see the
        king.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Now Absalom was praised as the most handsome man in all Israel. He
        was flawless from head to foot. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'He cut his hair only once a year, and then only because it was so
        heavy. When he weighed it out, it came to five pounds![[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '14:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>200 shekels </b>[2.3 kilograms] <b>by the royal standard.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "He had three sons and one daughter. His daughter\u2019s name was
        Tamar, and she was very beautiful.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Absalom lived in Jerusalem for two years, but he never got to see
        the king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Then Absalom sent for Joab to ask him to intercede for him, but Joab
        refused to come. Absalom sent for him a second time, but again Joab refused
        to come. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "So Absalom said to his servants, \u201CGo and set fire to Joab\u2019s
        barley field, the field next to mine.\u201D So they set his field on fire,
        as Absalom had commanded.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then Joab came to Absalom at his house and demanded, \u201CWhy did
        your servants set my field on fire?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "And Absalom replied, \u201CBecause I wanted you to ask the king why
        he brought me back from Geshur if he didn\u2019t intend to see me. I might
        as well have stayed there. Let me see the king; if he finds me guilty of
        anything, then let him kill me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: So Joab told the king what Absalom had said. Then at last David summoned
        Absalom, who came and bowed low before the king, and the king kissed him.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Absalom\u2019s Rebellion"
      title: "Absalom\u2019s Rebellion"
      number: 1
      content: '  After this, Absalom bought a chariot and horses, and he hired fifty
        bodyguards to run ahead of him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'He got up early every morning and went out to the gate of the city.
        When people brought a case to the king for judgment, Absalom would ask where
        in Israel they were from, and they would tell him their tribe. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then Absalom would say, \u201CYou\u2019ve really got a strong case
        here! It\u2019s too bad the king doesn\u2019t have anyone to hear it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I wish I were the judge. Then everyone could bring their cases to
        me for judgment, and I would give them justice!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When people tried to bow before him, Absalom wouldn\u2019t let them.
        Instead, he took them by the hand and kissed them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Absalom did this with everyone who came to the king for judgment,
        and so he stole the hearts of all the people of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "After four years,[[COMMENT(0)]] Absalom said to the king, \u201CLet
        me go to Hebron to offer a sacrifice to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and
        fulfill a vow I made to him. "
      comments:
      - number: '15:7 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads <b>forty years.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "For while your servant was at Geshur in Aram, I promised to sacrifice
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> in Hebron[[COMMENT(0)]] if he would bring
        me back to Jerusalem.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:8 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts; Hebrew lacks <b>in Hebron.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D the king told him. \u201CGo and fulfill your
        vow.\u201DSo Absalom went to Hebron. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "But while he was there, he sent secret messengers to all the tribes
        of Israel to stir up a rebellion against the king. \u201CAs soon as you hear
        the ram\u2019s horn,\u201D his message read, \u201Cyou are to say, \u2018Absalom
        has been crowned king in Hebron.\u2019\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'He took 200 men from Jerusalem with him as guests, but they knew
        nothing of his intentions. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: David Escapes from Jerusalem'
      title: David Escapes from Jerusalem
      number: 12
      content: "While Absalom was offering the sacrifices, he sent for Ahithophel,
        one of David\u2019s counselors who lived in Giloh. Soon many others also
        joined Absalom, and the conspiracy gained momentum.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "A messenger soon arrived in Jerusalem to tell David, \u201CAll Israel
        has joined Absalom in a conspiracy against you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CThen we must flee at once, or it will be too late!\u201D David
        urged his men. \u201CHurry! If we get out of the city before Absalom arrives,
        both we and the city of Jerusalem will be spared from disaster.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CWe are with you,\u201D his advisers replied. \u201CDo what
        you think is best.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So the king and all his household set out at once. He left no one
        behind except ten of his concubines to look after the palace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The king and all his people set out on foot, pausing at the last
        house '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "to let all the king\u2019s men move past to lead the way. There were
        600 men from Gath who had come with David, along with the king\u2019s bodyguard.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Kerethites and Pelethites.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then the king turned and said to Ittai, a leader of the men from
        Gath, \u201CWhy are you coming with us? Go on back to King Absalom, for you
        are a guest in Israel, a foreigner in exile. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "You arrived only recently, and should I force you today to wander
        with us? I don\u2019t even know where we will go. Go on back and take your
        kinsmen with you, and may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> show you his unfailing
        love and faithfulness.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:20 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>and may unfailing love and
          faithfulness go with you.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "But Ittai said to the king, \u201CI vow by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and by your own life that I will go wherever my lord the king goes, no matter
        what happens\u2014whether it means life or death.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "David replied, \u201CAll right, come with us.\u201D So Ittai and
        all his men and their families went along.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Everyone cried loudly as the king and his followers passed by. They
        crossed the Kidron Valley and then went out toward the wilderness.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Zadok and all the Levites also came along, carrying the Ark of the
        Covenant of God. They set down the Ark of God, and Abiathar offered sacrifices[[COMMENT(0)]]
        until everyone had passed out of the city.  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:24 '
        content: Or <b>Abiathar went up.</b>
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Then the king instructed Zadok to take the Ark of God back into the
        city. \u201CIf the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sees fit,\u201D David said,
        \u201Che will bring me back to see the Ark and the Tabernacle[[COMMENT(0)]]
        again. "
      comments:
      - number: '15:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>and his dwelling place.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "But if he is through with me, then let him do what seems best to
        him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "The king also told Zadok the priest, \u201CLook,[[COMMENT(0)]] here
        is my plan. You and Abiathar[[COMMENT(1)]] should return quietly to the city
        with your son Ahimaaz and Abiathar\u2019s son Jonathan. "
      comments:
      - number: '15:27a '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>Are you a seer? </b>or <b>Do
          you see?</b>
      - number: '15:27b '
        content: Hebrew lacks <b>and Abiathar; </b>compare 15:29.
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "I will stop at the shallows of the Jordan River[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        wait there for a report from you.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '15:28 '
        content: Hebrew <b>at the crossing points of the wilderness.</b>
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'So Zadok and Abiathar took the Ark of God back to the city and stayed
        there.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'David walked up the road to the Mount of Olives, weeping as he went.
        His head was covered and his feet were bare as a sign of mourning. And the
        people who were with him covered their heads and wept as they climbed the
        hill. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "When someone told David that his adviser Ahithophel was now backing
        Absalom, David prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, let Ahithophel
        give Absalom foolish advice!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'When David reached the summit of the Mount of Olives where people
        worshiped God, Hushai the Arkite was waiting there for him. Hushai had torn
        his clothing and put dirt on his head as a sign of mourning. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "But David told him, \u201CIf you go with me, you will only be a burden. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Return to Jerusalem and tell Absalom, \u2018I will now be your adviser,
        O king, just as I was your father\u2019s adviser in the past.\u2019 Then
        you can frustrate and counter Ahithophel\u2019s advice. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Zadok and Abiathar, the priests, will be there. Tell them about the
        plans being made in the king\u2019s palace, "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "and they will send their sons Ahimaaz and Jonathan to tell me what
        is going on.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "So David\u2019s friend Hushai returned to Jerusalem, getting there
        just as Absalom arrived."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David and Ziba'
      title: David and Ziba
      number: 1
      content: '  When David had gone a little beyond the summit of the Mount of
        Olives, Ziba, the servant of Mephibosheth,[[COMMENT(0)]] was waiting there
        for him. He had two donkeys loaded with 200 loaves of bread, 100 clusters
        of raisins, 100 bunches of summer fruit, and a wineskin full of wine.  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:1 '
        content: <b>Mephibosheth </b>is another name for Merib-baal.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CWhat are these for?\u201D the king asked Ziba.Ziba replied,
        \u201CThe donkeys are for the king\u2019s people to ride on, and the bread
        and summer fruit are for the young men to eat. The wine is for those who
        become exhausted in the wilderness.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CAnd where is Mephibosheth, Saul\u2019s grandson?\u201D the
        king asked him.\u201CHe stayed in Jerusalem,\u201D Ziba replied. \u201CHe
        said, \u2018Today I will get back the kingdom of my grandfather Saul.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: Shimei Curses David'
      title: Shimei Curses David
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CIn that case,\u201D the king told Ziba, \u201CI give you everything
        Mephibosheth owns.\u201D\u201CI bow before you,\u201D Ziba replied. \u201CMay
        I always be pleasing to you, my lord the king.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "As King David came to Bahurim, a man came out of the village cursing
        them. It was Shimei son of Gera, from the same clan as Saul\u2019s family. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "He threw stones at the king and the king\u2019s officers and all
        the mighty warriors who surrounded him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CGet out of here, you murderer, you scoundrel!\u201D he shouted
        at David. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is paying you back for all
        the bloodshed in Saul\u2019s clan. You stole his throne, and now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has given it to your son Absalom. At last you will taste some of your own
        medicine, for you are a murderer!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CWhy should this dead dog curse my lord the king?\u201D Abishai
        son of Zeruiah demanded. \u201CLet me go over and cut off his head!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CNo!\u201D the king said. \u201CWho asked your opinion, you
        sons of Zeruiah! If the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has told him to curse
        me, who are you to stop him?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then David said to Abishai and to all his servants, \u201CMy own
        son is trying to kill me. Doesn\u2019t this relative of Saul[[COMMENT(0)]]
        have even more reason to do so? Leave him alone and let him curse, for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has told him to do it. "
      comments:
      - number: '16:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>this Benjaminite.</b>
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "And perhaps the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will see that I am being
        wronged[[COMMENT(0)]] and will bless me because of these curses today.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '16:12 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads <b>see my iniquity.</b>
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'So David and his men continued down the road, and Shimei kept pace
        with them on a nearby hillside, cursing and throwing stones and dirt at David.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Ahithophel Advises Absalom'
      title: Ahithophel Advises Absalom
      number: 14
      content: 'The king and all who were with him grew weary along the way, so they
        rested when they reached the Jordan River.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:14 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 17:16); Hebrew reads <b>when they
          reached their destination.</b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Meanwhile, Absalom and all the army of Israel arrived at Jerusalem,
        accompanied by Ahithophel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When David\u2019s friend Hushai the Arkite arrived, he went immediately
        to see Absalom. \u201CLong live the king!\u201D he exclaimed. \u201CLong
        live the king!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CIs this the way you treat your friend David?\u201D Absalom
        asked him. \u201CWhy aren\u2019t you with him?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CI\u2019m here because I belong to the man who is chosen by
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and by all the men of Israel,\u201D Hushai
        replied. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CAnd anyway, why shouldn\u2019t I serve you? Just as I was your
        father\u2019s adviser, now I will be your adviser!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Then Absalom turned to Ahithophel and asked him, \u201CWhat should
        I do next?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Ahithophel told him, \u201CGo and sleep with your father\u2019s concubines,
        for he has left them here to look after the palace. Then all Israel will
        know that you have insulted your father beyond hope of reconciliation, and
        they will throw their support to you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "So they set up a tent on the palace roof where everyone could see
        it, and Absalom went in and had sex with his father\u2019s concubines.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Absalom followed Ahithophel\u2019s advice, just as David had done.
        For every word Ahithophel spoke seemed as wise as though it had come directly
        from the mouth of God."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: '
      title: 
      number: 1
      content: "  Now Ahithophel urged Absalom, \u201CLet me choose 12,000 men to
        start out after David tonight. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'I will catch up with him while he is weary and discouraged. He and
        his troops will panic, and everyone will run away. Then I will kill only
        the king, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "and I will bring all the people back to you as a bride returns to
        her husband. After all, it is only one man\u2019s life that you seek.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Then you will be at peace with all the people.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '17:3 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>like the return of all is the
          man whom you seek.</b>
    - name: "4: Hushai Counters Ahithophel\u2019s Advice"
      title: "Hushai Counters Ahithophel\u2019s Advice"
      number: 4
      content: 'This plan seemed good to Absalom and to all the elders of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "But then Absalom said, \u201CBring in Hushai the Arkite. Let\u2019s
        see what he thinks about this.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "When Hushai arrived, Absalom told him what Ahithophel had said. Then
        he asked, \u201CWhat is your opinion? Should we follow Ahithophel\u2019s
        advice? If not, what do you suggest?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CWell,\u201D Hushai replied to Absalom, \u201Cthis time Ahithophel
        has made a mistake. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "You know your father and his men; they are mighty warriors. Right
        now they are as enraged as a mother bear who has been robbed of her cubs.
        And remember that your father is an experienced man of war. He won\u2019t
        be spending the night among the troops. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "He has probably already hidden in some pit or cave. And when he comes
        out and attacks and a few of your men fall, there will be panic among your
        troops, and the word will spread that Absalom\u2019s men are being slaughtered. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Then even the bravest soldiers, though they have the heart of a lion,
        will be paralyzed with fear. For all Israel knows what a mighty warrior your
        father is and how courageous his men are.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CI recommend that you mobilize the entire army of Israel, bringing
        them from as far away as Dan in the north and Beersheba in the south. That
        way you will have an army as numerous as the sand on the seashore. And I
        advise that you personally lead the troops. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "When we find David, we\u2019ll fall on him like dew that falls on
        the ground. Then neither he nor any of his men will be left alive. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And if David were to escape into some town, you will have all Israel
        there at your command. Then we can take ropes and drag the walls of the town
        into the nearest valley until every stone is torn down.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Hushai Warns David to Escape'
      title: Hushai Warns David to Escape
      number: 14
      content: "Then Absalom and all the men of Israel said, \u201CHushai\u2019s
        advice is better than Ahithophel\u2019s.\u201D For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had determined to defeat the counsel of Ahithophel, which really was the
        better plan, so that he could bring disaster on Absalom!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Hushai told Zadok and Abiathar, the priests, what Ahithophel had
        said to Absalom and the elders of Israel and what he himself had advised
        instead. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CQuick!\u201D he told them. \u201CFind David and urge him not
        to stay at the shallows of the Jordan River[[COMMENT(0)]] tonight. He must
        go across at once into the wilderness beyond. Otherwise he will die and his
        entire army with him.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>at the crossing points of the wilderness.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Jonathan and Ahimaaz had been staying at En-rogel so as not to be
        seen entering and leaving the city. Arrangements had been made for a servant
        girl to bring them the message they were to take to King David. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'But a boy spotted them at En-rogel, and he told Absalom about it.
        So they quickly escaped to Bahurim, where a man hid them down inside a well
        in his courtyard. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "The man\u2019s wife put a cloth over the top of the well and scattered
        grain on it to dry in the sun; so no one suspected they were there.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When Absalom\u2019s men arrived, they asked her, \u201CHave you seen
        Ahimaaz and Jonathan?\u201DThe woman replied, \u201CThey were here, but they
        crossed over the brook.\u201D Absalom\u2019s men looked for them without
        success and returned to Jerusalem.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then the two men crawled out of the well and hurried on to King David.
        \u201CQuick!\u201D they told him, \u201Ccross the Jordan tonight!\u201D And
        they told him how Ahithophel had advised that he be captured and killed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So David and all the people with him went across the Jordan River
        during the night, and they were all on the other bank before dawn.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'When Ahithophel realized that his advice had not been followed, he
        saddled his donkey, went to his hometown, set his affairs in order, and hanged
        himself. He died there and was buried in the family tomb.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'David soon arrived at Mahanaim. By now, Absalom had mobilized the
        entire army of Israel and was leading his troops across the Jordan River. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Absalom had appointed Amasa as commander of his army, replacing Joab,
        who had been commander under David. (Amasa was Joab\u2019s cousin. His father
        was Jether,[[COMMENT(0)]] an Ishmaelite.[[COMMENT(1)]] His mother, Abigail
        daughter of Nahash, was the sister of Joab\u2019s mother, Zeruiah.) "
      comments:
      - number: '17:25a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Ithra, </b>a variant spelling of Jether.
      - number: '17:25b '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Chr 2:17); Hebrew reads
          <b>an Israelite.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Absalom and the Israelite army set up camp in the land of Gilead.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When David arrived at Mahanaim, he was warmly greeted by Shobi son
        of Nahash, who came from Rabbah of the Ammonites, and by Makir son of Ammiel
        from Lo-debar, and by Barzillai of Gilead from Rogelim. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'They brought sleeping mats, cooking pots, serving bowls, wheat and
        barley, flour and roasted grain, beans, lentils, '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "honey, butter, sheep, goats, and cheese for David and those who were
        with him. For they said, \u201CYou must all be very hungry and tired and
        thirsty after your long march through the wilderness.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Absalom\u2019s Defeat and Death"
      title: "Absalom\u2019s Defeat and Death"
      number: 1
      content: '  David now mustered the men who were with him and appointed generals
        and captains[[COMMENT(0)]] to lead them. '
      comments:
      - number: '18:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>appointed commanders of thousands and commanders of hundreds.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He sent the troops out in three groups, placing one group under Joab,
        one under Joab\u2019s brother Abishai son of Zeruiah, and one under Ittai,
        the man from Gath. The king told his troops, \u201CI am going out with you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "But his men objected strongly. \u201CYou must not go,\u201D they
        urged. \u201CIf we have to turn and run\u2014and even if half of us die\u2014it
        will make no difference to Absalom\u2019s troops; they will be looking only
        for you. You are worth 10,000 of us,[[COMMENT(0)]] and it is better that
        you stay here in the town and send help if we need it.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:3 '
        content: As in two Hebrew manuscripts and some Greek and Latin manuscripts;
          most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>Now there are 10,000 like us.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CIf you think that\u2019s the best plan, I\u2019ll do it,\u201D
        the king answered. So he stood alongside the gate of the town as all the
        troops marched out in groups of hundreds and of thousands.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "And the king gave this command to Joab, Abishai, and Ittai: \u201CFor
        my sake, deal gently with young Absalom.\u201D And all the troops heard the
        king give this order to his commanders.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'So the battle began in the forest of Ephraim, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "and the Israelite troops were beaten back by David\u2019s men. There
        was a great slaughter that day, and 20,000 men laid down their lives. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The battle raged all across the countryside, and more men died because
        of the forest than were killed by the sword.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "During the battle, Absalom happened to come upon some of David\u2019s
        men. He tried to escape on his mule, but as he rode beneath the thick branches
        of a great tree, his hair[[COMMENT(0)]] got caught in the tree. His mule
        kept going and left him dangling in the air. "
      comments:
      - number: '18:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>his head.</b>
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "One of David\u2019s men saw what had happened and told Joab, \u201CI
        saw Absalom dangling from a great tree.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CWhat?\u201D Joab demanded. \u201CYou saw him there and didn\u2019t
        kill him? I would have rewarded you with ten pieces of silver[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and a hero\u2019s belt!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 [shekels] of silver, </b>about 4 ounces or 114 grams
          in weight.
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CI would not kill the king\u2019s son for even a thousand pieces
        of silver,[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D the man replied to Joab. \u201CWe all heard
        the king say to you and Abishai and Ittai, \u2018For my sake, please spare
        young Absalom.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: '18:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1,000 [shekels] of silver, </b>about 25 pounds or 11.4
          kilograms in weight.
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And if I had betrayed the king by killing his son\u2014and the king
        would certainly find out who did it\u2014you yourself would be the first
        to abandon me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CEnough of this nonsense,\u201D Joab said. Then he took three
        daggers and plunged them into Absalom\u2019s heart as he dangled, still alive,
        in the great tree. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Ten of Joab\u2019s young armor bearers then surrounded Absalom and
        killed him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then Joab blew the ram\u2019s horn, and his men returned from chasing
        the army of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "They threw Absalom\u2019s body into a deep pit in the forest and
        piled a great heap of stones over it. And all Israel fled to their homes.  "
      comments: []
    - name: "18: David Mourns Absalom\u2019s Death"
      title: "David Mourns Absalom\u2019s Death"
      number: 18
      content: "During his lifetime, Absalom had built a monument to himself in the
        King\u2019s Valley, for he said, \u201CI have no son to carry on my name.\u201D
        He named the monument after himself, and it is known as Absalom\u2019s Monument
        to this day.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then Zadok\u2019s son Ahimaaz said, \u201CLet me run to the king
        with the good news that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has rescued him from
        his enemies.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CNo,\u201D Joab told him, \u201Cit wouldn\u2019t be good news
        to the king that his son is dead. You can be my messenger another time, but
        not today.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then Joab said to a man from Ethiopia,[[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CGo tell
        the king what you have seen.\u201D The man bowed and ran off.  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:21 '
        content: 'Hebrew <b>from Cush; </b>similarly in 18:23, 31, 32.  '
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "But Ahimaaz continued to plead with Joab, \u201CWhatever happens,
        please let me go, too.\u201D\u201CWhy should you go, my son?\u201D Joab replied.
        \u201CThere will be no reward for your news.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CYes, but let me go anyway,\u201D he begged.Joab finally said,
        \u201CAll right, go ahead.\u201D So Ahimaaz took the less demanding route
        by way of the plain and ran to Mahanaim ahead of the Ethiopian.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'While David was sitting between the inner and outer gates of the
        town, the watchman climbed to the roof of the gateway by the wall. As he
        looked, he saw a lone man running toward them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "He shouted the news down to David, and the king replied, \u201CIf
        he is alone, he has news.\u201DAs the messenger came closer, "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "the watchman saw another man running toward them. He shouted down,
        \u201CHere comes another one!\u201DThe king replied, \u201CHe also will have
        news.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CThe first man runs like Ahimaaz son of Zadok,\u201D the watchman
        said.\u201CHe is a good man and comes with good news,\u201D the king replied.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Then Ahimaaz cried out to the king, \u201CEverything is all right!\u201D
        He bowed before the king with his face to the ground and said, \u201CPraise
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God, who has handed over the rebels
        who dared to stand against my lord the king.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CWhat about young Absalom?\u201D the king demanded. \u201CIs
        he all right?\u201DAhimaaz replied, \u201CWhen Joab told me to come, there
        was a lot of commotion. But I didn\u2019t know what was happening.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201CWait here,\u201D the king told him. So Ahimaaz stepped aside.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then the man from Ethiopia arrived and said, \u201CI have good news
        for my lord the king. Today the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has rescued you
        from all those who rebelled against you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u201CWhat about young Absalom?\u201D the king demanded. \u201CIs
        he all right?\u201DAnd the Ethiopian replied, \u201CMay all of your enemies,
        my lord the king, both now and in the future, share the fate of that young
        man!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]The king was overcome with emotion. He went up to
        the room over the gateway and burst into tears. And as he went, he cried,
        \u201CO my son Absalom! My son, my son Absalom! If only I had died instead
        of you! O Absalom, my son, my son.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: '18:33 '
        content: '  Verse 18:33 is numbered 19:1 in Hebrew text.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Joab Rebukes the King'
      title: Joab Rebukes the King
      number: 1
      content: '    [[COMMENT(0)]]Word soon reached Joab that the king was weeping
        and mourning for Absalom. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:1 '
        content: '  Verses 19:1-43 are numbered 19:2-44 in Hebrew text.  '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "As all the people heard of the king\u2019s deep grief for his son,
        the joy of that day\u2019s victory was turned into deep sadness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'They crept back into the town that day as though they were ashamed
        and had deserted in battle. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "The king covered his face with his hands and kept on crying, \u201CO
        my son Absalom! O Absalom, my son, my son!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then Joab went to the king\u2019s room and said to him, \u201CWe
        saved your life today and the lives of your sons, your daughters, and your
        wives and concubines. Yet you act like this, making us feel ashamed of ourselves. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'You seem to love those who hate you and hate those who love you.
        You have made it clear today that your commanders and troops mean nothing
        to you. It seems that if Absalom had lived and all of us had died, you would
        be pleased. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Now go out there and congratulate your troops, for I swear by the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> that if you don\u2019t go out, not a single one
        of them will remain here tonight. Then you will be worse off than ever before.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So the king went out and took his seat at the town gate, and as the
        news spread throughout the town that he was there, everyone went to him.Meanwhile,
        the Israelites who had supported Absalom fled to their homes. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "And throughout all the tribes of Israel there was much discussion
        and argument going on. The people were saying, \u201CThe king rescued us
        from our enemies and saved us from the Philistines, but Absalom chased him
        out of the country. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Now Absalom, whom we anointed to rule over us, is dead. Why not ask
        David to come back and be our king again?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then King David sent Zadok and Abiathar, the priests, to say to the
        elders of Judah, \u201CWhy are you the last ones to welcome back the king
        into his palace? For I have heard that all Israel is ready. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "You are my relatives, my own tribe, my own flesh and blood! So why
        are you the last ones to welcome back the king?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And David told them to tell Amasa, \u201CSince you are my own flesh
        and blood, like Joab, may God strike me and even kill me if I do not appoint
        you as commander of my army in his place.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: "14: David\u2019s Return to Jerusalem"
      title: "David\u2019s Return to Jerusalem"
      number: 14
      content: "Then Amasa[[COMMENT(0)]] convinced all the men of Judah, and they
        responded unanimously. They sent word to the king, \u201CReturn to us, and
        bring back all who are with you.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '19:14 '
        content: Or <b>David; </b>Hebrew reads <b>he.</b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So the king started back to Jerusalem. And when he arrived at the
        Jordan River, the people of Judah came to Gilgal to meet him and escort him
        across the river. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Shimei son of Gera, the man from Bahurim in Benjamin, hurried across
        with the men of Judah to welcome King David. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "A thousand other men from the tribe of Benjamin were with him, including
        Ziba, the chief servant of the house of Saul, and Ziba\u2019s fifteen sons
        and twenty servants. They rushed down to the Jordan to meet the king. "
      comments: []
    - name: "18: David\u2019s Mercy to Shimei"
      title: "David\u2019s Mercy to Shimei"
      number: 18
      content: "They crossed the shallows of the Jordan to bring the king\u2019s
        household across the river, helping him in every way they could.As the king
        was about to cross the river, Shimei fell down before him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CMy lord the king, please forgive me,\u201D he pleaded. \u201CForget
        the terrible thing your servant did when you left Jerusalem. May the king
        put it out of his mind. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "I know how much I sinned. That is why I have come here today, the
        very first person in all Israel[[COMMENT(0)]] to greet my lord the king.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '19:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the house of Joseph.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then Abishai son of Zeruiah said, \u201CShimei should die, for he
        cursed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anointed king!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CWho asked your opinion, you sons of Zeruiah!\u201D David exclaimed.
        \u201CWhy have you become my adversary[[COMMENT(0)]] today? This is not a
        day for execution, for today I am once again the king of Israel!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '19:22 '
        content: Or <b>my prosecutor.</b>
    - name: "23: David\u2019s Kindness to Mephibosheth"
      title: "David\u2019s Kindness to Mephibosheth"
      number: 23
      content: "Then, turning to Shimei, David vowed, \u201CYour life will be spared.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Now Mephibosheth,[[COMMENT(0)]] Saul\u2019s grandson, came down from
        Jerusalem to meet the king. He had not cared for his feet, trimmed his beard,
        or washed his clothes since the day the king left Jerusalem. "
      comments:
      - number: '19:24 '
        content: <b>Mephibosheth </b>is another name for Merib-baal.
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CWhy didn\u2019t you come with me, Mephibosheth?\u201D the king
        asked him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Mephibosheth replied, \u201CMy lord the king, my servant Ziba deceived
        me. I told him, \u2018Saddle my donkey[[COMMENT(0)]] so I can go with the
        king.\u2019 For as you know I am crippled. "
      comments:
      - number: '19:26 '
        content: As in Greek, Syriac, and Latin versions; Hebrew reads <b>I will
          saddle a donkey for myself.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Ziba has slandered me by saying that I refused to come. But I know
        that my lord the king is like an angel of God, so do what you think is best. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "All my relatives and I could expect only death from you, my lord,
        but instead you have honored me by allowing me to eat at your own table!
        What more can I ask?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CYou\u2019ve said enough,\u201D David replied. \u201CI\u2019ve
        decided that you and Ziba will divide your land equally between you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: "30: David\u2019s Kindness to Barzillai"
      title: "David\u2019s Kindness to Barzillai"
      number: 30
      content: "\u201CGive him all of it,\u201D Mephibosheth said. \u201CI am content
        just to have you safely back again, my lord the king!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'Barzillai of Gilead had come down from Rogelim to escort the king
        across the Jordan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "He was very old\u2014eighty years of age\u2014and very wealthy. He
        was the one who had provided food for the king during his stay in Mahanaim. "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "\u201CCome across with me and live in Jerusalem,\u201D the king said
        to Barzillai. \u201CI will take care of you there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CNo,\u201D he replied, \u201CI am far too old to go with the
        king to Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'I am eighty years old today, and I can no longer enjoy anything.
        Food and wine are no longer tasty, and I cannot hear the singers as they
        sing. I would only be a burden to my lord the king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Just to go across the Jordan River with the king is all the honor
        I need! '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Then let me return again to die in my own town, where my father and
        mother are buried. But here is your servant, my son Kimham. Let him go with
        my lord the king and receive whatever you want to give him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "\u201CGood,\u201D the king agreed. \u201CKimham will go with me,
        and I will help him in any way you would like. And I will do for you anything
        you want.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'So all the people crossed the Jordan with the king. After David had
        blessed Barzillai and kissed him, Barzillai returned to his own home.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: An Argument over the King'
      title: An Argument over the King
      number: 40
      content: 'The king then crossed over to Gilgal, taking Kimham with him. All
        the troops of Judah and half the troops of Israel escorted the king on his
        way.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "But all the men of Israel complained to the king, \u201CThe men of
        Judah stole the king and didn\u2019t give us the honor of helping take you,
        your household, and all your men across the Jordan.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "The men of Judah replied, \u201CThe king is one of our own kinsmen.
        Why should this make you angry? We haven\u2019t eaten any of the king\u2019s
        food or received any special favors!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "\u201CBut there are ten tribes in Israel,\u201D the others replied.
        \u201CSo we have ten times as much right to the king as you do. What right
        do you have to treat us with such contempt? Weren\u2019t we the first to
        speak of bringing him back to be our king again?\u201D The argument continued
        back and forth, and the men of Judah spoke even more harshly than the men
        of Israel."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Revolt of Sheba'
      title: The Revolt of Sheba
      number: 1
      content: "  There happened to be a troublemaker there named Sheba son of Bicri,
        a man from the tribe of Benjamin. Sheba blew a ram\u2019s horn and began
        to chant:\u201CDown with the dynasty of David!We have no interest in the
        son of Jesse.Come on, you men of Israel,back to your homes!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'So all the men of Israel deserted David and followed Sheba son of
        Bicri. But the men of Judah stayed with their king and escorted him from
        the Jordan River to Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'When David came to his palace in Jerusalem, he took the ten concubines
        he had left to look after the palace and placed them in seclusion. Their
        needs were provided for, but he no longer slept with them. So each of them
        lived like a widow until she died.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then the king told Amasa, \u201CMobilize the army of Judah within
        three days, and report back at that time.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'So Amasa went out to notify Judah, but it took him longer than the
        time he had been given.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then David said to Abishai, \u201CSheba son of Bicri is going to
        hurt us more than Absalom did. Quick, take my troops and chase after him
        before he gets into a fortified town where we can\u2019t reach him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "So Abishai and Joab,[[COMMENT(0)]] together with the king\u2019s
        bodyguard[[COMMENT(1)]] and all the mighty warriors, set out from Jerusalem
        to go after Sheba. "
      comments:
      - number: '20:7a '
        content: "Hebrew <b>So Joab\u2019s men.</b>"
      - number: '20:7b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Kerethites and Pelethites; </b>also in 20:23.
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'As they arrived at the great stone in Gibeon, Amasa met them. Joab
        was wearing his military tunic with a dagger strapped to his belt. As he
        stepped forward to greet Amasa, he slipped the dagger from its sheath.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>As he stepped forward, it fell out.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CHow are you, my cousin?\u201D Joab said and took him by the
        beard with his right hand as though to kiss him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Amasa didn\u2019t notice the dagger in his left hand, and Joab stabbed
        him in the stomach with it so that his insides gushed out onto the ground.
        Joab did not need to strike again, and Amasa soon died. Joab and his brother
        Abishai left him lying there and continued after Sheba.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "One of Joab\u2019s young men shouted to Amasa\u2019s troops, \u201CIf
        you are for Joab and David, come and follow Joab.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "But Amasa lay in his blood in the middle of the road, and Joab\u2019s
        man saw that everyone was stopping to stare at him. So he pulled him off
        the road into a field and threw a cloak over him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "With Amasa\u2019s body out of the way, everyone went on with Joab
        to capture Sheba son of Bicri.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Meanwhile, Sheba traveled through all the tribes of Israel and eventually
        came to the town of Abel-beth-maacah. All the members of his own clan, the
        Bicrites,[[COMMENT(0)]] assembled for battle and followed him into the town. '
      comments:
      - number: '20:14 '
        content: As in Greek and Latin versions; Hebrew reads <b>All the Berites.</b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "When Joab\u2019s forces arrived, they attacked Abel-beth-maacah.
        They built a siege ramp against the town\u2019s fortifications and began
        battering down the wall. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But a wise woman in the town called out to Joab, \u201CListen to
        me, Joab. Come over here so I can talk to you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "As he approached, the woman asked, \u201CAre you Joab?\u201D\u201CI
        am,\u201D he replied.So she said, \u201CListen carefully to your servant.\u201D\u201CI\u2019m
        listening,\u201D he said.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then she continued, \u201CThere used to be a saying, \u2018If you
        want to settle an argument, ask advice at the town of Abel.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "I am one who is peace loving and faithful in Israel. But you are
        destroying an important town in Israel.[[COMMENT(0)]] Why do you want to
        devour what belongs to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a town that is a mother in Israel.</b>
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "And Joab replied, \u201CBelieve me, I don\u2019t want to devour or
        destroy your town! "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "That\u2019s not my purpose. All I want is a man named Sheba son of
        Bicri from the hill country of Ephraim, who has revolted against King David.
        If you hand over this one man to me, I will leave the town in peace.\u201D\u201CAll
        right,\u201D the woman replied, \u201Cwe will throw his head over the wall
        to you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then the woman went to all the people with her wise advice, and they
        cut off Sheba\u2019s head and threw it out to Joab. So he blew the ram\u2019s
        horn and called his troops back from the attack. They all returned to their
        homes, and Joab returned to the king at Jerusalem.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Now Joab was the commander of the army of Israel. Benaiah son of
        Jehoiada was captain of the king\u2019s bodyguard. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Adoniram[[COMMENT(0)]] was in charge of forced labor. Jehoshaphat
        son of Ahilud was the royal historian. '
      comments:
      - number: '20:24 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 1 Kgs 4:6; 5:14); Hebrew reads <b>Adoram.</b>
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Sheva was the court secretary. Zadok and Abiathar were the priests. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "And Ira, a descendant of Jair, was David\u2019s personal priest."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David Avenges the Gibeonites'
      title: David Avenges the Gibeonites
      number: 1
      content: "  There was a famine during David\u2019s reign that lasted for three
        years, so David asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> about it. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said, \u201CThe famine has come because Saul and his family are guilty of
        murdering the Gibeonites.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'So the king summoned the Gibeonites. They were not part of Israel
        but were all that was left of the nation of the Amorites. The people of Israel
        had sworn not to kill them, but Saul, in his zeal for Israel and Judah, had
        tried to wipe them out. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "David asked them, \u201CWhat can I do for you? How can I make amends
        so that you will bless the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s people again?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CWell, money can\u2019t settle this matter between us and the
        family of Saul,\u201D the Gibeonites replied. \u201CNeither can we demand
        the life of anyone in Israel.\u201D\u201CWhat can I do then?\u201D David
        asked. \u201CJust tell me and I will do it for you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then they replied, \u201CIt was Saul who planned to destroy us, to
        keep us from having any place at all in the territory of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So let seven of Saul\u2019s sons be handed over to us, and we will
        execute them before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> at Gibeon, on the mountain
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u201D</smallcaps>\u201CAll
        right,\u201D the king said, \u201CI will do it.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '21:6 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 21:9); Hebrew reads <b>at Gibeah of
          Saul, the chosen of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The king spared Jonathan\u2019s son Mephibosheth,[[COMMENT(0)]] who
        was Saul\u2019s grandson, because of the oath David and Jonathan had sworn
        before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: '21:7 '
        content: <b>Mephibosheth </b>is another name for Merib-baal.
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But he gave them Saul\u2019s two sons Armoni and Mephibosheth, whose
        mother was Rizpah daughter of Aiah. He also gave them the five sons of Saul\u2019s
        daughter Merab,[[COMMENT(0)]] the wife of Adriel son of Barzillai from Meholah. "
      comments:
      - number: '21:8 '
        content: As in a few Hebrew and Greek manuscripts and Syriac version (see
          also 1 Sam 18:19); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>Michal.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'The men of Gibeon executed them on the mountain before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        So all seven of them died together at the beginning of the barley harvest.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Then Rizpah daughter of Aiah, the mother of two of the men, spread
        burlap on a rock and stayed there the entire harvest season. She prevented
        the scavenger birds from tearing at their bodies during the day and stopped
        wild animals from eating them at night. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "When David learned what Rizpah, Saul\u2019s concubine, had done, "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'he went to the people of Jabesh-gilead and retrieved the bones of
        Saul and his son Jonathan. (When the Philistines had killed Saul and Jonathan
        on Mount Gilboa, the people of Jabesh-gilead stole their bodies from the
        public square of Beth-shan, where the Philistines had hung them.) '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'So David obtained the bones of Saul and Jonathan, as well as the
        bones of the men the Gibeonites had executed.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Battles against Philistine Giants'
      title: Battles against Philistine Giants
      number: 14
      content: "Then the king ordered that they bury the bones in the tomb of Kish,
        Saul\u2019s father, at the town of Zela in the land of Benjamin. After that,
        God ended the famine in the land.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Once again the Philistines were at war with Israel. And when David
        and his men were in the thick of battle, David became weak and exhausted. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Ishbi-benob was a descendant of the giants[[COMMENT(0)]]; his bronze
        spearhead weighed more than seven pounds,[[COMMENT(1)]] and he was armed
        with a new sword. He had cornered David and was about to kill him. '
      comments:
      - number: '21:16a '
        content: Or <b>a descendant of the Rapha; </b>also in 21:18, 20, 22.
      - number: '21:16b '
        content: Hebrew <b>300 [shekels] </b>[3.4 kilograms].
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But Abishai son of Zeruiah came to David\u2019s rescue and killed
        the Philistine. Then David\u2019s men declared, \u201CYou are not going out
        to battle with us again! Why risk snuffing out the light of Israel?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'After this, there was another battle against the Philistines at Gob.
        As they fought, Sibbecai from Hushah killed Saph, another descendant of the
        giants.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "During another battle at Gob, Elhanan son of Jair[[COMMENT(0)]] from
        Bethlehem killed the brother of Goliath of Gath.[[COMMENT(1)]] The handle
        of his spear was as thick as a weaver\u2019s beam!  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:19a '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 20:5; Hebrew reads <b>son of Jaare-oregim.</b>
      - number: '21:19b '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 20:5; Hebrew reads <b>killed Goliath
          of Gath.</b>
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'In another battle with the Philistines at Gath, they encountered
        a huge man[[COMMENT(0)]] with six fingers on each hand and six toes on each
        foot, twenty-four in all, who was also a descendant of the giants. '
      comments:
      - number: '21:20 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 20:6; Hebrew reads <b>a Midianite.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "But when he defied and taunted Israel, he was killed by Jonathan,
        the son of David\u2019s brother Shimea.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:21 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 20:7; Hebrew reads <b>Shimei, </b>a
          variant spelling of Shimea.
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: These four Philistines were descendants of the giants of Gath, but
        David and his warriors killed them.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: David\u2019s Song of Praise"
      title: "David\u2019s Song of Praise"
      number: 1
      content: '  David sang this song to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> on the
        day the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rescued him from all his enemies and
        from Saul. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He sang:\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is my rock, my fortress,
        and my savior;  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'my God is my rock, in whom I find protection.He is my shield, the
        power that saves me,and my place of safety.He is my refuge, my savior,the
        one who saves me from violence.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'I called on the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, who is worthy of praise,and
        he saved me from my enemies.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CThe waves of death overwhelmed me;floods of destruction swept
        over me.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The grave[[COMMENT(0)]] wrapped its ropes around me;death laid a
        trap in my path.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Sheol.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'But in my distress I cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>;yes,
        I cried to my God for help.He heard me from his sanctuary;my cry reached
        his ears.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CThen the earth quaked and trembled.The foundations of the heavens
        shook;they quaked because of his anger.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Smoke poured from his nostrils;fierce flames leaped from his mouth.Glowing
        coals blazed forth from him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He opened the heavens and came down;dark storm clouds were beneath
        his feet.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Mounted on a mighty angelic being,[[COMMENT(0)]] he flew,soaring[[COMMENT(1)]]
        on the wings of the wind.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:11a '
        content: Hebrew <b>a cherub.</b>
      - number: '22:11b '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts (see also Ps 18:10); other Hebrew
          manuscripts read <b>appearing.</b>
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'He shrouded himself in darkness,veiling his approach with dense rain
        clouds.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'A great brightness shone around him,and burning coals[[COMMENT(0)]]
        blazed forth.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:13 '
        content: Or <b>and lightning bolts.</b>
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> thundered from heaven;the voice of
        the Most High resounded.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'He shot arrows and scattered his enemies;his lightning flashed, and
        they were confused.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Then at the command of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,at the blast
        of his breath,the bottom of the sea could be seen,and the foundations of
        the earth were laid bare.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CHe reached down from heaven and rescued me;he drew me out of
        deep waters.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'He rescued me from my powerful enemies,from those who hated me and
        were too strong for me.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'They attacked me at a moment when I was in distress,but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        supported me.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'He led me to a place of safety;he rescued me because he delights
        in me.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rewarded me for doing right;he restored
        me because of my innocence.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'For I have kept the ways of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>;I have
        not turned from my God to follow evil.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'I have followed all his regulations;I have never abandoned his decrees.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'I am blameless before God;I have kept myself from sin.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rewarded me for doing right.He has
        seen my innocence.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CTo the faithful you show yourself faithful;to those with integrity
        you show integrity.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'To the pure you show yourself pure,but to the crooked you show yourself
        shrewd.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'You rescue the humble,but your eyes watch the proud and humiliate
        them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, you are my lamp.The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lights up my darkness.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'In your strength I can crush an army;with my God I can scale any
        wall.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CGod\u2019s way is perfect.All the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        promises prove true.He is a shield for all who look to him for protection.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'For who is God except the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?Who but our
        God is a solid rock?  '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'God is my strong fortress,and he makes my way perfect.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'He makes me as surefooted as a deer,enabling me to stand on mountain
        heights.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'He trains my hands for battle;he strengthens my arm to draw a bronze
        bow.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'You have given me your shield of victory;your help[[COMMENT(0)]]
        has made me great.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:36 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls; Masoretic Text reads <b>your answering.</b>
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'You have made a wide path for my feetto keep them from slipping.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "\u201CI chased my enemies and destroyed them;I did not stop until
        they were conquered.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'I consumed them;I struck them down so they did not get up;they fell
        beneath my feet.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'You have armed me with strength for the battle;you have subdued my
        enemies under my feet.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'You placed my foot on their necks.I have destroyed all who hated
        me.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'They looked for help, but no one came to their rescue.They even cried
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, but he refused to answer.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'I ground them as fine as the dust of the earth;I trampled them[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the gutter like dirt.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:43 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls (see also Ps 18:42); Masoretic Text reads
          <b>I crushed and trampled them.</b>
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "\u201CYou gave me victory over my accusers.You preserved me as the
        ruler over nations;people I don\u2019t even know now serve me.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'Foreign nations cringe before me;as soon as they hear of me, they
        submit.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: 'They all lose their courageand come trembling[[COMMENT(0)]] from
        their strongholds.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:46 '
        content: As in parallel text at Ps 18:45; Hebrew reads <b>come girding themselves.</b>
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives! Praise to my Rock!May
        God, the Rock of my salvation, be exalted!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'He is the God who pays back those who harm me;he brings down the
        nations under me  '
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: 'and delivers me from my enemies.You hold me safe beyond the reach
        of my enemies;you save me from violent opponents.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'For this, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, I will praise you among
        the nations;I will sing praises to your name.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "You give great victories to your king;you show unfailing love to
        your anointed,to David and all his descendants forever.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: David\u2019s Last Words"
      title: "David\u2019s Last Words"
      number: 1
      content: "  These are the last words of David:\u201CDavid, the son of Jesse,
        speaks\u2014David, the man who was raised up so high,David, the man anointed
        by the God of Jacob,David, the sweet psalmist of Israel.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:1 '
        content: Or <b>the favorite subject of the songs of Israel; </b>or <b>the
          favorite of the Strong One of Israel.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CThe Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> speaks through
        me;his words are upon my tongue.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "The God of Israel spoke.The Rock of Israel said to me:\u2018The one
        who rules righteously,who rules in the fear of God,  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "is like the light of morning at sunrise,like a morning without clouds,like
        the gleaming of the sunon new grass after rain.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CIs it not my family God has chosen?Yes, he has made an everlasting
        covenant with me.His agreement is arranged and guaranteed in every detail.He
        will ensure my safety and success.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'But the godless are like thorns to be thrown away,for they tear the
        hand that touches them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: "7: David\u2019s Mightiest Warriors"
      title: "David\u2019s Mightiest Warriors"
      number: 7
      content: "One must use iron tools to chop them down;they will be totally consumed
        by fire.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "These are the names of David\u2019s mightiest warriors. The first
        was Jashobeam the Hacmonite,[[COMMENT(0)]] who was leader of the Three[[COMMENT(1)]]\u2014the
        three mightiest warriors among David\u2019s men. He once used his spear to
        kill 800 enemy warriors in a single battle.[[COMMENT(2)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:8a '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 11:11; Hebrew reads <b>Josheb-basshebeth
          the Tahkemonite.</b>
      - number: '23:8b '
        content: As in Greek and Latin versions (see also 1 Chr 11:11); the meaning
          of the Hebrew is uncertain.
      - number: '23:8c '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Chr 11:11); the meaning
          of the Hebrew is uncertain, though it might be rendered <b>the Three. It
          was Adino the Eznite who killed 800 men at one time.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Next in rank among the Three was Eleazar son of Dodai, a descendant
        of Ahoah. Once Eleazar and David stood together against the Philistines when
        the entire Israelite army had fled. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He killed Philistines until his hand was too tired to lift his sword,
        and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave him a great victory that day. The
        rest of the army did not return until it was time to collect the plunder!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Next in rank was Shammah son of Agee from Harar. One time the Philistines
        gathered at Lehi and attacked the Israelites in a field full of lentils.
        The Israelite army fled, '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'but Shammah[[COMMENT(0)]] held his ground in the middle of the field
        and beat back the Philistines. So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> brought
        about a great victory.  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>he.</b>
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Once during the harvest, when David was at the cave of Adullam, the
        Philistine army was camped in the valley of Rephaim. The Three (who were
        among the Thirty\u2014an elite group among David\u2019s fighting men) went
        down to meet him there. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'David was staying in the stronghold at the time, and a Philistine
        detachment had occupied the town of Bethlehem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "David remarked longingly to his men, \u201COh, how I would love some
        of that good water from the well by the gate in Bethlehem.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So the Three broke through the Philistine lines, drew some water
        from the well by the gate in Bethlehem, and brought it back to David. But
        he refused to drink it. Instead, he poured it out as an offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: "17: David\u2019s Thirty Mighty Men"
      title: "David\u2019s Thirty Mighty Men"
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> forbid that I should drink
        this!\u201D he exclaimed. \u201CThis water is as precious as the blood of
        these men[[COMMENT(0)]] who risked their lives to bring it to me.\u201D So
        David did not drink it. These are examples of the exploits of the Three.  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shall I drink the blood of these men?</b>
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Abishai son of Zeruiah, the brother of Joab, was the leader of the
        Thirty.[[COMMENT(0)]] He once used his spear to kill 300 enemy warriors in
        a single battle. It was by such feats that he became as famous as the Three. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:18 '
        content: As in a few Hebrew manuscripts and Syriac version; most Hebrew manuscripts
          read <b>the Three.</b>
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Abishai was the most famous of the Thirty[[COMMENT(0)]] and was their
        commander, though he was not one of the Three.  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:19 '
        content: As in Syriac version; Hebrew reads <b>the Three.</b>
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'There was also Benaiah son of Jehoiada, a valiant warrior[[COMMENT(0)]]
        from Kabzeel. He did many heroic deeds, which included killing two champions[[COMMENT(1)]]
        of Moab. Another time, on a snowy day, he chased a lion down into a pit and
        killed it. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:20a '
        content: Or <b>son of Jehoiada, son of Ish-hai.</b>
      - number: '23:20b '
        content: Hebrew <b>two of Ariel.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Once, armed only with a club, he killed an imposing Egyptian warrior
        who was armed with a spear. Benaiah wrenched the spear from the Egyptian\u2019s
        hand and killed him with it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Deeds like these made Benaiah as famous as the Three mightiest warriors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'He was more honored than the other members of the Thirty, though
        he was not one of the Three. And David made him captain of his bodyguard.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Other members of the Thirty included:Asahel, Joab\u2019s brother;Elhanan
        son of Dodo from Bethlehem;  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Shammah from Harod;Elika from Harod;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Helez from Pelon[[COMMENT(0)]];Ira son of Ikkesh from Tekoa;  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:26 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 11:27 (see also 1 Chr 27:10); Hebrew
          reads <b>from Palti.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Abiezer from Anathoth;Sibbecai[[COMMENT(0)]] from Hushah;  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:27 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Chr 11:29); Hebrew reads
          <b>Mebunnai.</b>
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Zalmon from Ahoah;Maharai from Netophah;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Heled[[COMMENT(0)]] son of Baanah from Netophah;Ithai[[COMMENT(1)]]
        son of Ribai from Gibeah (in the land of Benjamin);  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:29a '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts (see also 1 Chr 11:30); most Hebrew
          manuscripts read <b>Heleb.</b>
      - number: '23:29b '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 11:31; Hebrew reads <b>Ittai.</b>
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Benaiah from Pirathon;Hurai[[COMMENT(0)]] from Nahale-gaash[[COMMENT(1)]];  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:30a '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Chr 11:32); Hebrew reads
          <b>Hiddai.</b>
      - number: '23:30b '
        content: Or <b>from the ravines of Gaash.</b>
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'Abi-albon from Arabah;Azmaveth from Bahurim;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Eliahba from Shaalbon;the sons of Jashen;Jonathan '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'son of Shagee[[COMMENT(0)]] from Harar;Ahiam son of Sharar from Harar;  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:33 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 11:34; Hebrew reads <b>Jonathan, Shammah;
          </b>some Greek manuscripts read <b>Jonathan son of Shammah.</b>
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'Eliphelet son of Ahasbai from Maacah;Eliam son of Ahithophel from
        Giloh;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Hezro from Carmel;Paarai from Arba;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Igal son of Nathan from Zobah;Bani from Gad;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'Zelek from Ammon;Naharai from Beeroth, the armor bearer of Joab son
        of Zeruiah;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'Ira from Jattir;Gareb from Jattir;  '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: Uriah the Hittite.There were thirty-seven in all.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: David Takes a Census'
      title: David Takes a Census
      number: 1
      content: "  Once again the anger of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> burned
        against Israel, and he caused David to harm them by taking a census. \u201CGo
        and count the people of Israel and Judah,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told him.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So the king said to Joab and the commanders[[COMMENT(0)]] of the
        army, \u201CTake a census of all the tribes of Israel\u2014from Dan in the
        north to Beersheba in the south\u2014so I may know how many people there
        are.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:2 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 24:4 and 1 Chr 21:2); Hebrew reads
          <b>Joab the commander.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "But Joab replied to the king, \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God let you live to see a hundred times as many people as there are
        now! But why, my lord the king, do you want to do this?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'But the king insisted that they take the census, so Joab and the
        commanders of the army went out to count the people of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'First they crossed the Jordan and camped at Aroer, south of the town
        in the valley, in the direction of Gad. Then they went on to Jazer, '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'then to Gilead in the land of Tahtim-hodshi[[COMMENT(0)]] and to
        Dan-jaan and around to Sidon. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:6 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>to Gilead and to Kadesh in the land of the
          Hittites.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then they came to the fortress of Tyre, and all the towns of the
        Hivites and Canaanites. Finally, they went south to Judah[[COMMENT(0)]] as
        far as Beersheba.  '
      comments:
      - number: '24:7 '
        content: Or <b>they went to the Negev of Judah.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Having gone through the entire land for nine months and twenty days,
        they returned to Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: "9: Judgment for David\u2019s Sin"
      title: "Judgment for David\u2019s Sin"
      number: 9
      content: 'Joab reported the number of people to the king. There were 800,000
        capable warriors in Israel who could handle a sword, and 500,000 in Judah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "But after he had taken the census, David\u2019s conscience began
        to bother him. And he said to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CI have
        sinned greatly by taking this census. Please forgive my guilt, <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        for doing this foolish thing.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "The next morning the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came
        to the prophet Gad, who was David\u2019s seer. This was the message: "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CGo and say to David, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will give you three choices. Choose one of these punishments, and
        I will inflict it on you.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "So Gad came to David and asked him, \u201CWill you choose three[[COMMENT(0)]]
        years of famine throughout your land, three months of fleeing from your enemies,
        or three days of severe plague throughout your land? Think this over and
        decide what answer I should give the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who sent
        me.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:13 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 1 Chr 21:12); Hebrew reads <b>seven.</b>
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CI\u2019m in a desperate situation!\u201D David replied to Gad.
        \u201CBut let us fall into the hands of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        for his mercy is great. Do not let me fall into human hands.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent a plague upon Israel that
        morning, and it lasted for three days.[[COMMENT(0)]] A total of 70,000 people
        died throughout the nation, from Dan in the north to Beersheba in the south. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>for the designated time.</b>
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But as the angel was preparing to destroy Jerusalem, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        relented and said to the death angel, \u201CStop! That is enough!\u201D At
        that moment the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was by the threshing
        floor of Araunah the Jebusite.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: David Builds an Altar'
      title: David Builds an Altar
      number: 17
      content: "When David saw the angel, he said to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        \u201CI am the one who has sinned and done wrong! But these people are as
        innocent as sheep\u2014what have they done? Let your anger fall against me
        and my family.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "That day Gad came to David and said to him, \u201CGo up and build
        an altar to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> on the threshing floor of Araunah
        the Jebusite.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'So David went up to do what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded
        him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'When Araunah saw the king and his men coming toward him, he came
        and bowed before the king with his face to the ground. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CWhy have you come, my lord the king?\u201D Araunah asked.David
        replied, \u201CI have come to buy your threshing floor and to build an altar
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> there, so that he will stop the plague.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CTake it, my lord the king, and use it as you wish,\u201D Araunah
        said to David. \u201CHere are oxen for the burnt offering, and you can use
        the threshing boards and ox yokes for wood to build a fire on the altar. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "I will give it all to you, Your Majesty, and may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God accept your sacrifice.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "But the king replied to Araunah, \u201CNo, I insist on buying it,
        for I will not present burnt offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God that have cost me nothing.\u201D So David paid him fifty pieces of
        silver[[COMMENT(0)]] for the threshing floor and the oxen.  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 shekels of silver, </b>about 20 ounces or 570 grams
          in weight.
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: David built an altar there to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and
        sacrificed burnt offerings and peace offerings. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        answered his prayer for the land, and the plague on Israel was stopped.
      comments: []
